headline: Regina Sues Ex-Chairman Due to Fraud
abstract: LEAD: The Regina Company, a vacuum-cleaner maker, filed a lawsuit yesterday against a former top executive who pleaded guilty earlier this week to having falsified financial statements for the company in 1988.

headline: Business Inventories Rose 0.4% in November
abstract: LEAD: Business inventories rose four-tenths of 1 percent in November and sales rose at the same pace, the Government said today in a report that analysts said bodes well for the nation's economy.

headline: Boeing, Short of Workers, Borrows Some at Lockheed
abstract: LEAD: The Boeing Company, which has been struggling to meet demand for its new 747-400 jumbo jet, has turned to an uncommon solution to bolster its assembly lines: borrowing workers from another aircraft manufacturer.

headline: Europe Fires A New Shot In Trade War
abstract: LEAD: The European Community said today that American walnuts and dried prunes, peaches, apricots and papayas would be subject to punitive tariffs if its trade dispute with the United States was not settled soon.

headline: Sun Microsystems Shares to A.T.&T.
abstract: LEAD: Sun Microsystems Inc. said it would issue about 3.2 million more shares of its common stock to the American Telephone and Telegraph Company for about $79.1 million. The sale comes under the terms of a January 1988 agreement under which Sun can sell to A.T.&T., at Sun's option, newly issued shares equal to 15 percent of its total outstanding common shares.

headline: A&W: Prospering By Avoiding The Big Boys A&W Avoids the Big Boys
abstract: LEAD: There are lots of things that tiny A&W Brands Inc. just cannot do. It cannot hype its sales and brand awareness by getting McDonald's or Burger King to serve its root beer; a contract with the A&W restaurant chain prohibits the soft drink maker from selling to any other fountain operation.

headline: French Bank Settlement Called Near
abstract: LEAD: The four-month fight by the financier Georges Pebereau for control of Societe Generale, France's fourth-largest commercial bank, is apparently near an end.

headline: Microsoft Stake In Unix Maker
abstract: LEAD: The Microsoft Corporation said today that it would make a minority investment in the Santa Cruz Operation Inc., a privately held company that produces Unix system software.

headline: Allegheny Reinstates Merger
abstract: LEAD: Allegheny International, the Pittsburgh-based appliance maker, announced that it had signed a merger agreement yesterday with a suitor it had formerly rebuffed, Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette.

headline: As Major Prague Trial Opens, Moscow Presses a Softer Line
abstract: LEAD: As the playwright Vaclav Havel and eight other opposition figures prepare to go on trial Tuesday, the Czechoslovak Government is under pressure to expand political freedoms.

headline: Bush Won't Block Chip Unit's Sale
abstract: LEAD: President Bush has decided not to block the sale of the Monsanto Company's semiconductor subsidiary to one of the largest chemical companies in West Germany, the White House said today.

headline: Japan Official Unable to Be At Group of 7
abstract: LEAD: Japan's Finance Minister, Tatsuo Murayama, will not attend the meetings this weekend of the finance ministers of the United States and its major allies, casting doubts on what might be accomplished.

headline: Business Digest
abstract: LEAD:  Companies

headline: Soviets Are Glum About Kabul's Future
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Government offered a bleak picture today of the situation facing the Afghan Government as preparations continued for the completion of the Soviet troop withdrawal.

headline: Big Slices of Authority For 2 Brady Assistants
abstract: LEAD: Nicholas F. Brady is taking his own approach to organizing the upper echelons of the Treasury Department that he inherited from James A. Baker 3d.

headline: Bush Confers With Other Leaders After Funeral
abstract: LEAD: President Bush concluded his visit to Tokyo this morning, meeting with other leaders on East-West relations and regional tensions and offering an upbeat assessment of relations with the Far East as he prepared to leave for China.

headline: A Close Adviser to Indira Gandhi Was Investigated in Her Killing
abstract: LEAD: The Government disclosed today that a close aide to Prime Minister Indira Gandhi had been the subject of a special investigation after questions were raised about whether he played a role in Mrs. Gandhi's assassination.

headline: Senate Panel Moves Swiftly To Approve Trade Nominee
abstract: LEAD: The nomination of Carla A. Hills as the United States trade representative sailed through the Senate Finance Committee today after a confirmation hearing in which she said she would not hesitate to impose sanctions on countries that do not ''show results'' in reducing trade barriers that Washington deems unfair.

headline: Hitachi Sued By Motorola
abstract: LEAD: Motorola Inc. filed a lawsuit Wednesday charging that Hitachi Ltd. had infringed on several of its patents and was engaging in unfair competition in the sale of microprocessors. In the lawsuit filed in United

headline: Why Rolls-Royce Loves Its Bentley Photos of Malcolm Hart, director of sales and marketing of Rolls Royce Motor Cars, with a Bentley Turbo R (NYT/Jonathan Player); working at the bottom of a car at the Crewe factory, which turns out Bentley and Rolls-Royce models; checking the hides (NYT); graph of number of Bentleys sold, 1970-1988* (*Estimate) (Source: Company reports)
abstract: LEAD: The automotive accolades - ''hot,'' ''sporty,'' ''an incredible driving experience'' - are usually showered on the likes of Ferrari, Lamborghini and Porsche. But now, in auto magazines and among car enthusiasts, the praises are being heaped on a Bentley, long considered the stately first cousin of the Rolls

headline: Cuba Sugar Production
abstract: LEAD: Cuba announced a campaign today to increase sugar production to an all-time high over the next couple of years, mostly for export to socialist bloc countries.

headline: Purchasers Say Growth Is Lagging
abstract: LEAD: The nation's economic growth in February was the slowest in two years, a monthly survey of the nation's purchasing managers concluded.

headline: Leading Indicators Up by 0.6%
abstract: LEAD: The Government's principal economic-forecasting index climbed six-tenths of 1 percent in December, the eighth straight month in which it has reversed direction, the Commerce Department reported today.

headline: Concern Voiced on New Chief and Drug Trade
abstract: LEAD: The United States said today that it hoped the military coup in Paraguay was a step toward democracy, but American officials expressed grave concern about reports linking the leader of the coup to narcotics traffic.

headline: With Futures Under Fire, A Watchdog Feels the Heat
abstract: LEAD: In a majestic Senate committee room, flanked with ornate mirrors and decorated with impressive Victorian chandeliers, a Government official faces a panel of powerful lawmakers, who bombard her with complicated questions. The official is Wendy Gramm, chairwoman of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, and not only is she in the hot seat, so is her agency.

headline: Afghan Rebel Tactic: Shut Airports
abstract: LEAD: Afghan guerrillas plan to close airports as the first step to force the surrender of Afghanistan's cities, a guerrilla news organization said today.

headline: A Consortium Will Acquire Cooke's Cable TV Systems
abstract: LEAD: A consortium of cable operators said yesterday that it had agreed to acquire the cable systems owned by Jack Kent Cooke, which have a total of 700,000 subscribers. No price was disclosed.

headline: Shamrock Lifts Bid for Polaroid
abstract: LEAD: Shamrock Holdings Inc. said today that it would raise its offer for the Polaroid Corporation by $3, to $45 a share, and begin a proxy fight for control of the company's board. The revised offer is worth $3.1 billion.

headline: A City Where Apartheid Shows Its Gentler Face
abstract: LEAD: A semblance of normal life has returned to obscure some of the political tensions of this scenic coastal city, part of an area damaged by the social engineering of apartheid and nearly a decade of sporadic civil unrest.

headline: S.E.C. Picks Computer Bid
abstract: LEAD: After a delay of more than a two years, the Securities and Exchange Commission today awarded a $52 million contract to build its electronic data gathering, analysis and retrieval system, known as Edgar.

headline: Consultants Sue Andersen
abstract: LEAD: The Information Consulting Group, a consulting organization that specializes in the design and installation of computer systems, said today that it had filed a $300 million lawsuit against Arthur Andersen & Company, charging the Big Eight accounting firm with seeking to destroy I.C.G. by intimidating prospective employees and clients and by disparaging its principals.

headline: Chicago Board of Trade Challenges Rival Globex System
abstract: LEAD: With technology similar to that used in video games, the Chicago Board of Trade is seeking to challenge its smaller archrival, the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, in the computerized buying and selling of futures contracts.

headline: Sony Introduces Video Equipment
abstract: LEAD: The Sony Corporation introduced video equipment that it said uses 8-millimeter tape but has the same sharpness as products that use the wider Super VHS format. Sony said the new EV-S900 videotape recorder would be priced at $1,850 and the CCD-V900 combined camera-recorder at $1,880. Both will be available in Japan in April and in the United States in May or

headline: Ulster Protestants and Catholics Talk Secretly
abstract: LEAD: Leading politicians from four Protestant and Catholic parties in Northern Ireland have acknowledged secretly talking to each other since October about resuming a dialogue on ways out of the violence that has killed 2,700 people since 1969.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; Financial Officer Named President of Dean Foods
abstract: LEAD: The Dean Foods Company has named its chief financial officer, William D. Fischer, president and chief operating officer to fill the year-old void left by Howard M. Dean. Mr. Dean, the company's previous president, became chief executive officer in October 1987 and was elected chairman recently.

headline: Research Pioneer Quits Salomon Brothers Post
abstract: LEAD: Salomon Brothers Inc. has lost yet another important executive with the departure of Laszlo Birinyi Jr., who developed Wall Street's most detailed research on institutional stock trading patterns.

headline: U.S.-Canada Trade Talks Set
abstract: LEAD: Canada and the United States are about to begin new trade negotiations after receiving requests from American and Canadian companies to accelerate tariff reductions on more than 50 goods, trade officials say.

headline: Europe Inquiry On Asian Tapes
abstract: LEAD: The European Community's Executive Commission said today that it had begun an inquiry into imports of audio cassette tapes from Asia that are said to be for sale in the 12-nation trade bloc at below market prices.

headline: Stocks Move Lower and Dow Drops 3.93
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices moved lower yesterday and the Dow Jones industrial average suffered its fifth loss in the last six sessions. But more stocks on the New York Stock Exchange rose than fell.

headline: Pretoria Held to Create Namibia Rebel Group
abstract: LEAD: A Namibian opposition leader has asserted that South Africa is creating a rebel Namibian group similar to groups aided in the past by South Africa in Mozambique and in Angola.

headline: Talking Business with Cornstein of Finlay Enterprises; A Bright Outlook For Retail Jewelry
abstract: LEAD: Jewelry retailing is undergoing a round of restructuring and consolidation. A good example was the recent management buyout of Finlay Fine Jewelry, a New York-based operator of leased jewelry concessions in department stores, by an investor group led by Harold S. Geneen, the former chairman of the ITT Corporation.

headline: Japan to Let Contract On Disputed Jet Project
abstract: LEAD: The Japan Defense Agency said today that it would sign an $86 million contract on Thursday with Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, the prime developer of the FSX fighter, even though Japan has not reached a formal agreement about the aircraft with the United States.

headline: China Denounces Petition Drive For Political Prisoners' Amnesty
abstract: LEAD: In a sign of Government concern at growing calls for human rights, China's official media today attacked a dissident petition drive for an amnesty of China's political prisoners.

headline: Irving Officer Gets New Post
abstract: LEAD: The Bank of New York Company announced yesterday that Samuel F. Chevalier, 55 years old, had been appointed a vice chairman of both the bank and the holding company. Mr. Chevalier is the president of the Irving Bank Corporation and a vice chairman of its banking subsidiary. The Bank of New York acquired Irving in

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Acceptance Insurance Holdings Inc., Omaha, and KCP Holding Co., a privately held company, reached a preliminary agreement to merge, with Acceptance being the surviving company. Acceptance shareholders who wish to sell their shares will be paid $16.50. In response, Stoneridge Resources Inc. of Bloomfield, Mich., raised its offer for Acceptance to $18 a share from $16.50.

headline: S.E.C. Seeks Wider Fines
abstract: LEAD: The head of the enforcement division of the Securities and Exchange Commission said today that the Federal agency would ask Congress to pass legislation allowing the S.E.C. to seek monetary penalties for all civil violations of the Federal securities laws. At present, the S.E.C. can seek monetary penalties only for civil charges of insider trading.

headline: Iran Petrochemical Unit
abstract: LEAD: Iran is determined to complete the petrochemical plant at Bandar Khomeini despite the disruption of construction during the Persian Gulf war. Ahmad Rahgozar, managing director of Iran's National Petrochemical Company, quoted by the Iranian press agency, said the plant could be completed for a fraction of the cost of building a new one.

headline: Arabs Blacklist Hotel Chain Owner
abstract: LEAD: Arab officials organizing the economic boycott of Israel blacklisted the British-based owners of the Hilton International hotel chain. An official at the Damascus-based Arab Bureau for the Boycott of Israel said the Ladbroke Group, which owns Hilton, was blacklisted on Saturday. He said that under boycott rules all subsidiaries of a blacklisted group or company were included in the ban.

headline: Pretoria Says Apartheid Foe Worked as Its Spy Since '81
abstract: LEAD: The Government confirmed today that Olivia Forsyth, a former anti-apartheid militant who took refuge in the British Embassy in Angola last year, was a South African spy.

headline: The U.N. Today
abstract: LEAD:  General Assembly  Meets at 10:30 A.M.

headline: Shea & Gould Paring Office
abstract: LEAD: The law firm of Shea & Gould said yesterday that it would scale down its office in Los Angeles to ''a small nucleus.'' A third of the lawyers there announced earlier this week that they were defecting to the new firm of Myerson & Kuhn.

headline: Patents; A Sonic Buoy to Find Schools of Fish
abstract: LEAD: The Honda Electric Company of Aichi, Japan, won a patent this week for a sonic buoy that finds schools of fish by using sonar echoes.

headline: 48 on Bus Die in Ivory Coast
abstract: LEAD: A bus packed with schoolchildren toppled into a culvert during a thunderstorm on Saturday, and news reports said today that 48 passengers were killed and 75 injured. The storm had filled the culvert with water and many of the victims drowned, reports said.

headline: A Turning Point
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: 13 Palestinians Wounded on Eve of Holiday
abstract: LEAD: Thirteen Palestinians were reported shot and wounded today in clashes with soldiers in the occupied territories after Muslim fundamentalists declared a week of increased resistance to mark a religious holiday.

headline: Mariupol Journal; In Hometown, Stalin's Henchman Has Great Fall
abstract: LEAD: For years this city was held up as a model. It was heavily industrial, with two of the country's biggest steel plants. In addition, it bore the name of Andrei A. Zhdanov, one of the architects of the Stalinist system.

headline: Rebels Disrupting the Eradication of Coca in Peru
abstract: LEAD: A surge of leftist guerrilla activity is bringing new difficulties to a United States-backed campaign to eradicate coca production and break up drug trafficking gangs in Peru's main coca-growing region.

headline: I.B.M. to Settle Patent Suit
abstract: LEAD: The International Business Machines Corporation said today that it had agreed to settle a $100 million lawsuit contending that its personal computers had violated a basic patent on word processing held by a small Rockville, Md., company. The settlement calls for

headline: Iran Rebuffs Britain on Rushdie's Novel; U.S. Muslims Urge Ban
abstract: LEAD: Spokesmen for American Muslims yesterday urged fellow Muslims throughout the world ''to seek nonviolent but resolute means'' to end the furor over ''The Satanic Verses.'' But they demanded that Viking Penguin halt further publication of the novel.

headline: I.B.M. Expects Profits To Be Disappointing
abstract: LEAD: Undercutting the widespread belief that its 1989 earnings would be strong, the International Business Machines Corporation said yesterday that its first-quarter income would fall below analysts' expectations.

headline: Jefferies Credibility Is Assailed
abstract: LEAD: In several dramatic confrontations, defense lawyers yesterday assailed the credibility of Boyd L. Jefferies, the Government's main witness in the GAF Corporation stock manipulation trial and two other major securities cases.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; One-Stop Shopping To Reach Alumni
abstract: LEAD: Students at the Wharton School, the University of Pennsylvania's graduate school of business, have assembled the alumni magazines of seven top business schools into a unified advertising network called the Management Network.

headline: Kabul Journal; Voices of Urban Fear: War's End Is Worth a Deal
abstract: LEAD: Like many people in Kabul, Safaar Mohammad came here to escape the war. After Soviet aircraft bombed his village in northern Afghanistan in 1980, he walked across the mountains to the capital and set up a stall in the old bazaar. Now, at age 60, Mr. Mohammad believes that only providence can prevent the war from engulfing him again.

headline: Chairman Is Selected At Worlds of Wonder
abstract: LEAD: Worlds of Wonder Inc., the toy company that had a quick rise before entering bankruptcy proceedings in 1987, is getting a new chairman and chief executive as it nears the end of its reorganization.

headline: CBS Records to Buy Tree, Ending an Era in Nashville
abstract: LEAD: Tree International Publishing, the last country music publisher to be both owned and operated in Nashville, is being sold to CBS Records for more than $30 million.

headline: RJR Nabisco Stock Surges On U.S. Move
abstract: LEAD: The stock of RJR Nabisco Inc. rose sharply yesterday after Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Company announced an agreement with the staff of the Federal Trade Commission on the buyout firm's acquisition of RJR.

headline: In Autos, U.S. Makes Strides
abstract: LEAD: American auto makers have rung up six years of strong profits, including a record $11.2 billion for 1988. That is a remarkable performance for an industry that not long ago suffered severe losses in the face of competition from abroad. But it would be premature to conclude that Detroit has vanquished its rivals: in many crucial areas,

headline: Vietnamese Report Progress In Their Talks With Chinese
abstract: LEAD: Vietnam reported progress today in relations with Beijing and said the Vietnamese leader, Nguyen Van Linh, would go to India next week in the search for peace in Cambodia.

headline: Solidarity May Win 40% of Parliament
abstract: LEAD: Two weeks after the start of talks between the Government and the outlawed opposition, both sides say they have reached ''fundamental accord'' on allowing the Solidarity-led opposition to control as many as two-fifths of the seats in Parliament through pre-arranged elections.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; International Approach Of McCann
abstract: LEAD: WHEN the Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company introduced its new advertising campaign in 36 countries three years ago, it hewed to a single slogan: ''Goodyear, Take Me Home.''

headline: WPP Group Reports Big Jump in Earnings
abstract: LEAD: WPP Group, the marketing communications conglomerate, said its 1988 earnings more than tripled, to $71.8 million, or $1.96 a share, from $23.7 million, or $1.08 a share, in 1987. Gross revenues more than doubled, to $974.7 million in 1988 from $477.3 million in 1987.

headline: CUTS THREATENED IN AID TO ISRAEL
abstract: LEAD: Key members of Congress responsible for setting foreign aid levels say that Israel's treatment of Palestinians in the occupied territories is unacceptable and could weaken Congressional support for American aid to Israel.

headline: Sony to Expand Plant
abstract: LEAD: The Sony Corporation said Thursday that it would expand its television manufacturing plant at Bridgend in Wales, creating 300 jobs. The Japanese electronics company said the investment of $:36 million, or about $63 million, would make the 15-year-old factory one of the most advanced in the world. It said increased production of Trinitron color televisions and tubes would start in May.

headline: U.S. PRELATES OPEN TALKS IN VATICAN
abstract: LEAD: A long-awaited meeting of American Roman Catholic archbishops with Pope John Paul II and his Vatican aides opened here today with a warm welcome from the Pope and a denial by Bernardin Cardinal Gantin, who heads the Vatican's Congregation for Bishops, that the meeting would be confrontational.

headline: Farley Expects Shift by Pepperell
abstract: LEAD: The chairman of Farley Industries said he believed that West Point-Pepperell Inc.'s executives would change their hostile stance toward Farley's $48-a-share offer before a special shareholders meeting on Feb. 25.

headline: A 'Strong' Earthquake Hits Japan's Capital, Killing Man
abstract: LEAD: A strong earthquake hit the capital and much of northern Japan today, killing one person and injuring another, shaking buildings and briefly halting some train and airline service, officials said.

headline: BAKER PLANS VISIT TO MOSCOW IN MAY TO DISCUSS SUMMIT
abstract: LEAD: Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d said today that he would go to Moscow in May to discuss the resumption of strategic-arms negotiations and the prospects for President Bush's first summit meeting with Mikhail S. Gorbachev.

headline: Talking Deals; Joint Soviet Deal, But Based in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: ALVIN DUSKIN, like a number of other American businessmen, wants to take advantage of the opportunity to join with the Soviet Union in new ventures. But, unlike his compatriots, his headquarters for a joint company will be here, not there.

headline: Funeral's Shinto Rite: Specter of the Past
abstract: LEAD: Like the country that spawned it, the Shinto religion by whose rites Emperor Hirohito will be buried has taken many forms over the centuries.

headline: Interview on the Run For Top Job at Egghead
abstract: LEAD: Stuart M. Sloan, a Seattle retailing executive, was interviewing for a job for 14 years without realizing it. Three times a week, he and his jogging partner, Victor D. Alhadeff, run five miles and discuss business. In particular, they share an interest in Egghead Inc., a fast-growing chain of software stores founded by Mr.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Public-Service Ads
abstract: LEAD: As the airwaves become more crowded, public-service advertising finds itself crowded out of consumers' consciousnesses. So the S. I. Newhouse School of Public Communications at Syracuse University and Arbitron Ratings are sponsoring a seminar to help public-service advertisers and their agencies. The daylong conference, ''Great Ideas, New Directions,'' will be held at the Madison Hotel in Washington on April 4.

headline: Europe-Indonesia Deal
abstract: LEAD: The European Community has agreed to allow Indonesia to export 25.5 million knitted garments to the community this year, the largest quota granted to any supplier, a textile trade group said today. Hong Kong, previously the largest supplier of knitted garments to the 12-nation trading bloc, received a quota of 25.32 million pieces, said Chamrul Djafri, an executive of the Indonesian Textile Association.

headline: Iraq Said to Cut Oil Exports
abstract: LEAD: Iraq has cut its oil exports by 90,000 barrels a day in accordance with its new OPEC production quota of 2.64 million barrels a day, the official Iraqi news agency said today.

headline: Champion Spark Plug Gets Offer From Cooper Industries
abstract: LEAD: A bidding war for the Champion Spark Plug Company, owner of one of the world's most familiar brand names, seemed likely today after Cooper Industries said it intended to offer at least $21 a share, of $735 million, for the company.

headline: Bank Board Chief Assailed On Savings-Crisis Record
abstract: LEAD: An official of the General Accounting Office told a Congressional hearing today that the liabilities of the savings industry's insurance fund now exceed its assets by $56 billion, four times the total of a year ago.

headline: Factory Orders Up Strongly For December and Year
abstract: LEAD: Factory orders rose by 4.1 percent in December as American manufacturers, bolstered by a boom in export sales, posted their best showing last year since 1979.

headline: Carlyle Group Lifts Stake in Fairchild
abstract: LEAD: The Carlyle Group, a Washington investment firm, has raised its stake in Fairchild Industries to 13.5 percent from 9.9 percent. In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Carlyle said that ''based upon a review of available alternatives,'' it believed Fairchild's stock was an attractive investment at current market prices.

headline: 12 Die in Bombay in Anti-Rushdie Riot
abstract: LEAD: At least 12 people were killed and 40 wounded today when the police fired at Muslims rioting in Bombay against Salman Rushdie's novel, ''The Satanic Verses.''

headline: Penney Plans Sale Of Insurance Unit
abstract: LEAD: The J. C. Penney Company said that it had put its J. C. Penney Casualty Insurance Company up for sale and that it was holding preliminary talks with several companies. The giant retailer, based in Plano, Tex., said that it had decided to abandon the in-store insurance business because the expected synergy between the company's retail operations and personal financial services had failed to materialize.

headline: 'New Authoritarianism' Seen in Chinese Actions
abstract: LEAD: President Bush had an embarrassingly conspicuous front-row seat here Sunday to a spectacle that may have been inspired by a new theory that has come to be known as ''new authoritarianism.''

headline: Company's Aid to F.B.I. Reported
abstract: LEAD: The Government began its two-year undercover investigation of the nation's two largest commodities exchanges after a major agricultural company said it believed there was cheating by traders at the exchanges, people involved in the case said today.

headline: Hispanic Partnership Formed to Buy TV Stations
abstract: LEAD: Hoping to take advantage of tax incentives available to television station owners who sell to minority buyers, Herman Badillo, Geraldo Rivera and three other Hispanic partners yesterday announced the formation of a partnership to acquire and manage stations in various markets around the country.

headline: Soviets Say Afghan Deadline Is in Danger
abstract: LEAD: A top Soviet diplomat warned today that there is ''serious danger'' that his country will not meet the Feb. 15 deadline for withdrawing its last troops from Afghanistan.

headline: Rig Count Dips in Week
abstract: LEAD: The number of working oil and gas rigs fell last week by nine, to a total of 757, Baker Hughes Inc. reported. A year ago, the count was 983, the company said.

headline: Dollar Increases Sharply, Causing Fed Intervention
abstract: LEAD: The dollar rose sharply yesterday, prompting intervention by the Federal Reserve in an attempt to slow the rally.

headline: Moscow Journal; The Stalin Generation, Where Nostalgia Dies Hard
abstract: LEAD: He was 3 years old when his family was driven from its village near Kursk in 1929, during Stalin's campaign against the more prosperous peasants known as kulaks. His infant brother died in the exile.

headline: Rights Group Reports 1,000 Iran Executions
abstract: LEAD: Amnesty International said today that more than 1,000 political prisoners had been shot or hanged in Iran over the past six months in the biggest wave of executions there since the early 1980's.

headline: Needed Fast at Continental: Profits
abstract: LEAD: Of the many brickbats that the striking employees at Eastern Airlines have thrown at Frank Lorenzo, one most frequently heard is that he is a corporate raider interested in a fast buck who knows nothing about running an airline.

headline: FINANCE/NEW ISSUES;
abstract: LEAD: The Student Loan Marketing Association, known as Sallie Mae, is offering $450 million of short-term floating-rate notes due Aug. 10, through various securities dealers.

headline: Trade Deficit: Economists Gloomy
abstract: LEAD: After a long and agonizing battle that finally put the trade deficit on a downward course last year, the United States already confronts the prospect of seeing that progress slip away, many economists fear.

headline: Greenspan's Inflation Stance Spurs a Rally in the Dollar
abstract: LEAD: The dollar rose yesterday, spurred by strong anti-inflation comments by Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, and the absence of dollar-selling by central banks.

headline: Rushdie's Publisher Assails 'Censorship by Terrorism'
abstract: LEAD: A spokesman for Viking Penguin yesterday condemned ''censorship by terrorism and intimidation,'' and he coupled his remarks with criticism of the major bookstore chains that have pulled ''The Satanic Verses'' from their shelves.

headline: Ukraine Intellectuals Lead Challenge to Communists
abstract: LEAD: Ukrainians by the millions turned on their television sets the other night to witness a wondrous sight, a popular Ukrainian literary critic in fiery debate with a senior ideologist from the republic's Communist Party.

headline: Mozambique Seeks to Heal Young Minds
abstract: LEAD: Until last week, when Goncalves Sebastiao, 13 years old, returned here to his mother's reed hut, home had been but a distant memory blurred by the trauma of being an unwilling participant in war.

abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Regina Sues Ex-Chairman Due to Fraud
abstract: LEAD: The Regina Company, a vacuum-cleaner maker, filed a lawsuit yesterday against a former top executive who pleaded guilty earlier this week to having falsified financial statements for the company in 1988.

headline: Business Inventories Rose 0.4% in November
abstract: LEAD: Business inventories rose four-tenths of 1 percent in November and sales rose at the same pace, the Government said today in a report that analysts said bodes well for the nation's economy.

headline: Boeing, Short of Workers, Borrows Some at Lockheed
abstract: LEAD: The Boeing Company, which has been struggling to meet demand for its new 747-400 jumbo jet, has turned to an uncommon solution to bolster its assembly lines: borrowing workers from another aircraft manufacturer.

headline: Europe Fires A New Shot In Trade War
abstract: LEAD: The European Community said today that American walnuts and dried prunes, peaches, apricots and papayas would be subject to punitive tariffs if its trade dispute with the United States was not settled soon.

headline: Sun Microsystems Shares to A.T.&T.
abstract: LEAD: Sun Microsystems Inc. said it would issue about 3.2 million more shares of its common stock to the American Telephone and Telegraph Company for about $79.1 million. The sale comes under the terms of a January 1988 agreement under which Sun can sell to A.T.&T., at Sun's option, newly issued shares equal to 15 percent of its total outstanding common shares.

headline: A&W: Prospering By Avoiding The Big Boys A&W Avoids the Big Boys
abstract: LEAD: There are lots of things that tiny A&W Brands Inc. just cannot do. It cannot hype its sales and brand awareness by getting McDonald's or Burger King to serve its root beer; a contract with the A&W restaurant chain prohibits the soft drink maker from selling to any other fountain operation.

headline: French Bank Settlement Called Near
abstract: LEAD: The four-month fight by the financier Georges Pebereau for control of Societe Generale, France's fourth-largest commercial bank, is apparently near an end.

headline: Microsoft Stake In Unix Maker
abstract: LEAD: The Microsoft Corporation said today that it would make a minority investment in the Santa Cruz Operation Inc., a privately held company that produces Unix system software.

headline: Allegheny Reinstates Merger
abstract: LEAD: Allegheny International, the Pittsburgh-based appliance maker, announced that it had signed a merger agreement yesterday with a suitor it had formerly rebuffed, Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette.

headline: President Is Removed at Boston Company
abstract: LEAD: The Boston Company announced Friday that it had removed its president, James N. von Germeten, after having concluded that its after-tax earnings for the first three quarters of 1988 were overstated by $30 million - more than twice as much as a preliminary estimate.

headline: Light Touch For Channel On Business
abstract: LEAD: WHEN the National Broadcasting Company decided to create the Consumer News and Business Channel, its cable-television news service that will begin next month, it faced a problem familiar to package-goods manufacturers: differentiating the product from its competitors in the category.

headline: S.E.C.-Drexel Negotiations Are Said to Be at Impasse
abstract: LEAD: The Securities and Exchange Commission and Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. are at an impasse over how to settle the charges of securities law violations against the firm, a person directly involved in the case said yesterday.

headline: BankAmerica Payout: Signal of a Recovery
abstract: LEAD: Reaching a significant milestone on its road to recovery, the BankAmerica Corporation announced today that it would pay a dividend on its common stock for the first time in three years.

headline: Dow Up by 9.46; Institutional Buying Cited
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices rose moderately yesterday as the Dow Jones industrial average once again reached a post-crash high.

headline: Soviets Pledge Continued Aid to Afghan Leaders
abstract: LEAD: Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, visiting Kabul, pledged continued ''all-around assistance'' to Afghanistan's beleaguered Government, the Soviet press agency Tass said today.

headline: Income Rises at 3 Phone Companies
abstract: LEAD: The Pacific Telesis Group said yesterday that its earnings in the fourth quarter climbed by 66 percent from the corresponding period last year, which was depressed by several extraordinary items.

headline: Bond Prices Post Large Declines
abstract: LEAD: Treasury bond prices posted their biggest declines in more than three months yesterday, pushed lower because of tepid investor demand at an auction of new 30-year bonds and a drop in the dollar's value.

headline: 85-Truck Supply Convoy Reaches Besieged City, Kabul Officials Say
abstract: LEAD: The Afghan Government relieved pressure on the besieged city of Jalalabad today when a convoy of 85 supply trucks that had been delayed by guerrilla ambushes and by the destruction of a strategic bridge broke through to the city, according to Government officials here.

headline: A NAMIBIAN GROUP OPPOSES U.N. CUTS
abstract: LEAD: The head of the South-West Africa People's Organization called on the United Nations today not to cut back on its plans for a Namibian peacekeeping force.

headline: U S Sprint Accuses A.T.&T.
abstract: LEAD: The U S Sprint Communications Company yesterday accused the American Telephone and Telegraph Company of distributing misleading promotional materials to solicit long-distance telephone accounts for pay telephones.

headline: Dublin Journal; Fair Is City but Foul Is Air When Smog Creeps In
abstract: LEAD: The smog creeps menacingly through doors and windows here. It attacks throats and lungs. It sometimes invades Dublin to such a degree that night appears to fall by midday.

headline: U.S. Rig Count Declines
abstract: LEAD: The number of working rotary oil-drilling rigs in the United States fell by three, to 740, in the week ended Friday, Baker Hughes Inc. said today. There were 943 rigs working a year earlier. The rig counts show the number of rigs actively exploring for oil, not the number producing oil.

headline: Japan's Trade Surplus Drops to a 4-Year Low
abstract: LEAD: Japan's current account surplus in January tumbled to its lowest level in four years because of unexpectedly heavy spending abroad by Japanese tourists, the Government said today.

headline: HEALTH CARE'S HIGH COST

headline: Sears Agrees to Sell Coldwell Commercial
abstract: LEAD: Sears, Roebuck & Company has agreed to sell its Coldwell Banker Commercial Group to a group of investors for about $300 million.

headline: Blacks Battle Fellow Blacks in Natal
abstract: LEAD: The danger peaks around midnight, Xakile Duma said, when vigilantes stalk the streets of the black township of Imbali.

headline: Legacy of Mao Called 'Great Disaster'
abstract: LEAD: In one of the harshest official appraisals so far of Mao Zedong, a leading Chinese newspaper has said he brought great disasters to the Chinese people.

headline: Korean Leader Turns to Compromise
abstract: LEAD: When President Roh Tae Woo surprised South Korea and his own party this week by canceling a referendum on his first year in office, the country braced for more of the chaos and protests that have marked its uneasy transition to democracy.

headline: Schwab Weighs Buying Rose
abstract: LEAD: Charles Schwab & Company, the nation's largest discount brokerage firm, announced yesterday that it was discussing the purchase of the Rose & Company Investment Brokerage, a unit of the Chase Manhattan Corporation.

headline: Market Place; 2 Theorists Split On Elliott Wave
abstract: LEAD: A DECADE ago, Ralph N. Elliott was a forgotten stock market analyst. Then two men of different generations resurrected his ideas and gained growing public attention with the forecast that the 1980's would see a surging bull market, perhaps topping out in 1987 with the Dow Jones industrial average near 2,800.

headline: William Clay Ford Retires; Two in Family May Get Posts
abstract: LEAD: William Clay Ford, vice chairman of the Ford Motor Company, retired today from active management and several policy-making committees at the No. 2 auto maker. At the same time, he indicated that his son William Clay Ford Jr. and nephew Edsel Ford 2d would be appointed to committees of the board within the year.

headline: Williams Telecommunications to Buy Lightnet
abstract: LEAD: The Williams Telecommunications Group, a fast-growing digital telecommunications company, said today that it had signed an agreement to acquire Lightnet, another fiber-optics company, for about $365 million.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Networks vs. Cable: Battle Heating Up
abstract: LEAD: FACED with network television's first sustained attack against its effectiveness, cable television is responding with outwardly conciliatory tones, hoping to demonstrate that all television programmers share common ground when advertisers are casting a wary eye on their budgets. Yesterday, Robert H.

headline: Powerful Chip Due From Intel
abstract: LEAD: The Intel Corporation is preparing to provide details of an extremely powerful new chip for the microprocessor business.

headline: Nicaragua Devalues Currency
abstract: LEAD: The Sandinista Government devalued the currency and raised prices for petroleum products today for the third time this year. The devaluation, from 2,300 to 2,700 cordobas to the dollar, is part of economic measures designed to contain inflation that has reached an annual rate of 36,000 percent.

headline: For PC's, a New Class of Software
abstract: LEAD: As personal computers become more powerful and run several programs at once, a new class of software is emerging that will dramatically extend their usefulness.

headline: Economic Scene; Bush's Campaign On the Budget
abstract: LEAD: PRESIDENT BUSH has knocked Congress off balance by proposing an array of modest spending increases that allow him to redeem his campaign promises for ''building a better America'' while offering, in friendly fashion, to negotiate with Congress on a broad range of cuts in other programs. This week Mr.

headline: Top Avnet Executive Adds Chairman's Post
abstract: LEAD: Avnet Inc., the nation's largest semiconductor distributor, has elected Leon Machiz chairman and chief executive officer. He succeeds Anthony R. Hamilton, who died of cancer on Dec. 22.

headline: France Asks Slower Buying of Iranian Oil
abstract: LEAD: France quietly signaled its major oil companies today to slow the purchase of Iranian oil, according to the French news agency and oil industry sources here. It thus apparently joins a move by Japan, which has ordered similar cutbacks.

headline: Nippon Phone Releasing Data
abstract: LEAD: Japan's dominant phone company, under pressure from the Government, said Friday that it would disclose market information that would help its new long-distance competitors plan their strategies. The Nippon Telegraph and

headline: 12 Arabs Wounded in Uprising
abstract: LEAD: Israeli troops shot and wounded 12 Palestinian demonstrators today, and there were conflicting reports over responsibility for the overnight killing of a West Bank village leader.

headline: Price Riots Erupt in Venezuela
abstract: LEAD: Demonstrations against price increases across Venezuela turned violent today as thousands of protesters threw stones at the police, broke store windows and looted businesses. Hundreds of people were reported injured.

headline: Tax Watch
abstract: LEAD: EVEN people with the best-laid tax and financial plans may overlook a valuable deduction. In addition, few taxpayers anticipated the retroactive changes made by the Technical and Miscellaneous Revenue Act of 1988, but some of those changes provide opportunities for refunds.

headline: Imhausen Aide Says Concern Shipped Ecstasy Drug to U.S.
abstract: LEAD: A West German company suspected of playing a key role in building a poison-gas factory in Libya said today that it produced and shipped an illegal drug known as Ecstasy to the United States.

headline: Cape Verde: From Colony to a Success Story
abstract: LEAD: A visitor to this tidy, seaside capital finds services that are memories in the rest of Portuguese-speaking Africa - taxis, public telephones, garbage collection, bustling markets and restaurants offering fresh lobster.

headline: News Report Stirs Dispute
abstract: LEAD: Hemodynamics Inc., a Florida medical concern, has disclosed that a court has granted its request for a preliminary injunction against its former public relations concern.

headline: 2 Are Accused Of Intel Scheme
abstract: LEAD: The founder and an employee of Ulsi System Technology Inc., a start-up chip company in San Jose, Calif., were charged with conspiracy to steal trade secrets from the Intel Corporation.

headline: Soviets Say Armenian Invented Ordeal in Quake
abstract: LEAD: Tass, the Soviet press agency, said today that Aikaz Akopyan and his sister had ''apparently'' invented an account of his rescue last week after being trapped 35 days with five companions beneath the rubble of the Armenian earthquake.

headline: Chief Named by Texaco For Canadian Oil Unit
abstract: LEAD: Philip J. Cram will be carrying the flag of Texaco Inc. in Canada after the oil company sells its 78 percent interest in Texaco Canada Inc.

headline: U S West Unit In Consortium
abstract: LEAD: U S West International said today that it had formed a consortium to bid for what it said would be the world's biggest cable television franchise, in Hong Kong.

headline: Palme Killing: Suspect but No Motive
abstract: LEAD: After nearly three years, millions spent and hundreds of thousands of man-hours dedicated to the pursuit of theories of international conspiracy, the hunt for the killer of Prime Minister Olof Palme has apparently narrowed down to a ''lone, mad Swede.''

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Chiat/Day's Deal
abstract: LEAD: Chiat/Day said it had reached agreement with the management of Mojo MDA to pay $67.2 million for all the outstanding shares of the publicly held Australian advertising agency. The bid is still subject to approval by the United States Foreign Investment Review Board and by Mojo's shareholders.

headline: McDonald's Profit Rises
abstract: LEAD: The McDonald's Corporation said today that its earnings rose 16.8 percent, to $151.5 million, in the fourth quarter and that it planned to open 600 restaurants this year.

headline: Foreign Medical Workers Help Fight Afghan War's Legacy
abstract: LEAD: In a crowded ward at the Red Cross's Surgical Hospital for War Wounded the old Afghan lay immobile on his bed, his face and hands severely burned.

headline: Tenneco Unit Sale
abstract: LEAD: Tenneco Inc., the Houston-based diversified industrial corporation, said it had reached a definitive agreement to sell its Louisiana Intrastate Gas Corporation unit and related assets. Terms were not disclosed. The company is being acquired by a new corporation formed by Wasserstein Perella Partners, Gale L.

headline: Bhopal Tragedy: The Key Events
abstract: LEAD:  Dec. 3, 1984: Methyl isocyanate gas leaks from pesticides plant of Union Carbide India Ltd. in Bhopal, India. Final death toll is estimated at more than 3,500.  Dec. 7: Warren Anderson, chairman of Union Carbide, and Keshub Mahindra, chairman of Union Carbide India, are arrested on charges of negligence and corporate liability.

headline: 35 Nations Issue East-West Accord Assuring a Broad Range of Rights
abstract: LEAD: Thirty-five nations today made public a new East-West agreement that includes commitments for the protection of human rights, including freedom of association, religion, travel and emigration.

headline: Rushdie Is Still Planning to Visit U.S. Next Week
abstract: LEAD: A death sentence by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and other protests have not altered the plans of the novelist Salman Rushdie to come to the United States next week to promote ''The Satanic Verses,'' his American literary agent said yesterday.

headline: Market Place; A Sector Coughs: Are Others Sick?
abstract: LEAD: WITH leading computer companies sending out warnings of problems, the Wall Street view of corporate profits this year is growing more cautious.

headline: Rightists Blamed in Killing of 12 in Colombia
abstract: LEAD: The slayings this week of 12 members of a judicial commission that had apparently uncovered evidence on previous massacres has focused outrage on violent right-wing paramilitary groups and prompted a two-day protest strike by the nation's judges and court workers.

headline: Israelis Dispute Charge by U.S. Of Rights Abuse
abstract: LEAD: Israel said today that it saw no merit in the United States' assertion that there had been ''a substantial increase in human rights violations'' as a result of Israel's response to the Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.

headline: Afghan Rebel Leader Voices Confidence in Unifying a Fractious Movement
abstract: LEAD: He heads a government without a country under its control, and his Afghan partners often need to be reminded that their enemy is the Soviet-backed regime in Kabul instead of one another.

headline: Prod Leaders, Arabs Tell Israel
abstract: LEAD: The Arab uprising's underground leadership called on Israeli citizens today to prod their Government to negotiate with the Palestine Liberation Organization.

headline: Saudi Oil Production
abstract: LEAD: Saudi Arabia's oil output averaged 4.35 million barrels a day in the first two weeks of January, slightly below its newly assigned OPEC quota of 4.52 million barrels, Persian Gulf oil sources said today.

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Up a Bit
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds posted moderate gains yesterday, while bill rates plunged as the debt market tried to absorb conflicting economic data. One result was that institutional investors continued to stand aside, which reduced trading activity and may have exaggerated price moves.

headline: U.S. Study Praises Mexico's Drug Moves
abstract: LEAD: A State Department report on drug trafficking has praised the three-month-old Government of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari of Mexico for substantially increasing its anti-narcotics efforts, senior Administration officials said today.

headline: Afghan Army Fires on Guerrillas to Protect Convoy
abstract: LEAD: Afghan Army units resumed firing today on guerrillas hidden in the hills north of Kabul, ending almost two weeks of calm around the Afghan capital.

headline: South Africans Ban Protests In Support of 300 Prisoners
abstract: LEAD: The Government today banned all protest meetings intended to show solidarity with 300 black detainees who are refusing food to protest being held without charge.

headline: IRANIANS PROTEST OVER BANNED BOOK
abstract: LEAD: Thousands of people reportedly threw stones and waved pictures of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini outside the British Embassy in Teheran today in protest against a book that has been deemed offensive to Islam.

headline: Sri Lankan Authorities Begin Releasing Political Detainees
abstract: LEAD: The Government released more than 200 political prisoners today after the new President, Ranasinghe Premadasa, lifted a state of emergency in this ethnically troubled land, the military said.

headline: Paraguay Ponders Changes As Much Remains the Same
abstract: LEAD: With many questions about the future still unanswered, Paraguay returned rapidly to normal today after Friday's ouster of the country's long-ruling dictator, Gen. Alfredo Stroessner.

headline: Backing Seen For Globex
abstract: LEAD: The Commodity Futures Trading Commission, which polices futures exchanges, is expected to vote Thursday to approve a proposal by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange to begin the first computerized network available to futures traders around the world.

headline: Moscow to Get Academy of Jewish Learning
abstract: LEAD: Moscow, which got a new Jewish cultural center last week, will get a yeshiva this week, the first such academy of Jewish learning on Soviet soil in 60 years.

headline: Rights Group Criticizes U.S. Over Refugees in Indochina
abstract: LEAD: A human rights group has asserted in a report on Indochinese refugees that United States immigration and screening procedures are unfair. It also criticized Thailand, along with Malaysia and Hong Kong, for trying to shift the burden of asylum elsewhere through harsh policies toward refugees.

headline: Aetna Life to Sell Federated Investors
abstract: LEAD: Federated Investors Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of Aetna Life and Casualty, will be sold to a new company to be operated and primarily owned by Federated's management. headline: F.B.I. Commodities 'Sting': Fast Money, Secret Lives
abstract: LEAD: Few people at the Chicago Board of Trade took notice in December 1986 when a stocky man, who combed strands of hair over his head to conceal a bald spot, began working on the trading floor as a telephone clerk.

headline: U.S. Charges Russian With Spying And Says He Will Be Sent Home
abstract: LEAD: The United States said today that it was expelling a Soviet military attache who was detained Wednesday night and accused of espionage.

headline: Polaroid's 22% Buyback Plan Is Heavily Oversubscribed
abstract: LEAD: A day after a major victory in its effort to stay independent, the Polaroid Corporation said today that its offer to buy back 22 percent of its shares had been heavily oversubscribed.

headline: Federal Farm Credit Offering
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Farm Credit Funding Corporation is offering three-month, six-month and one-year bonds totaling $2.849 billion through the corporation itself and through various securities dealers. All the bonds are priced at par.

headline: Poland Tying Political Reform to Aid From West
abstract: LEAD: As talks continue on extensive reforms that could produce at least the appearance of power sharing between the Solidarity trade union and the Government, wildcat strikes are crippling the economy.

headline: Marietta Names Head Of Its Space Venture
abstract: LEAD: The Martin Marietta Corporation yesterday named Edward M. Browne to lead its commercial space venture.

headline: MAI Basic Move
abstract: LEAD: MAI Basic Four Inc. asked a Federal District Court judge to lift an order blocking its $20-a-share bid for Prime Computer Inc. In court documents responding to a judge's concerns, MAI Basic said Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. was confident it could raise $875 million to finance the takeover. Prime, based in Natick, Mass., said it would fight to keep the court order in place.

headline: Cubans Leaving Angola Look Back in Fondness
abstract: LEAD: With her brown hair in a ponytail and heart-shaped earrings in her ears, 19-year-old Vivian Hernandez Caballero of the Cuban women's antiaircraft battery is already preparing for a long-awaited reunion this week with her boyfriend in Havana.

headline: Judge Rules Mistrial in GAF Case
abstract: LEAD: In a serious embarrassment to Federal prosecutors in New York, a judge declared a mistrial yesterday in the GAF stock manipulation case, the first prosecution based on information from the insider-trading scandals of 1986.

headline: What's in a Japanese Name? For Many Women, Obscurity
abstract: LEAD: Reiko Sekiguchi is the name she was given at birth, and that is how she is addressed at social gatherings and scholarly conferences, on research papers, even on letters from her husband.

headline: Patents; Space Station Structure
abstract: LEAD: The National Aeronautics and Space Administration won patent approval this week for part of the structural skeleton of a space station. The skeleton, which consists of struts connected in a latticework of squares and tetrahedrons, would be outside the station's pressurized housing and would be used to mount monitoring instruments and other equipment.

headline: Drop in Europe Jobless
abstract: LEAD: The unemployment rate in the 12-nation European Community fell in December to 10 percent, its lowest level in more than five years, the community reported today. The jobless rate in November was 10.1 percent. The community last had an unemployment rate of 10 percent in the summer of 1983. Unemployment peaked at 11 percent in the fall of 1984.

headline: Your Money; Insurance Benefit: Low-Cost Loans
abstract: LEAD: When unexpected bills start to pile up, many financial advisers recommend that hard-pressed families take out a low-cost loan on their life insurance. Policyholders can borrow against 75 percent to 90 percent of the cash value of a life insurance policy and can even forgo repaying the loan and interest if they are willing to reduce insurance benefits.

headline: President to Succeed Roderick in USX Job
abstract: LEAD: The USX Corporation said yesterday that Charles A. Corry, its president, would succeed David M. Roderick as chairman and chief executive when Mr. Roderick retires on May 31 at age 65.

headline: Khomeini Urges Muslims to Kill Author of Novel
abstract: LEAD: Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran declared today that the author and publishers of a novel deemed offensive to Islam had been ''sentenced to death.'' The novelist, Salman Rushdie, author of ''The Satanic Verses,'' said he was taking the threat seriously.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; President Becomes Chief At Integrated Resources
abstract: LEAD: Arthur H. Goldberg, president and chief operating officer of Integrated Resources Inc. since 1973, has been elected chief executive of the company, succeeding Selig A. Zises, who will remain as chairman.

headline: Bond Yields at 7.2% to 7.75% For Carolina Power Agency
abstract: LEAD: The North Carolina Eastern Municipal Power Agency tentatively priced yesterday $429.55 million of power system revenue refunding bonds with a maximum yield of about 7.75 percent for an issue due in 2012.

headline: Hoechst Unit's Net Up 48%
abstract: LEAD: The Hoechst Celanese Corporation, a subsidiary of the West German chemical and pharmaceutical company Hoechst A.G., said this week that it had earned $250 million in 1988, up 48 percent from $169 million in 1987. Revenue last year was $5.68 billion, a 23 percent increase from $4.61 billion in 1987.

headline: MINERS IN POLAND GO BACK TO WORK
abstract: LEAD: Striking miners at a coal mine feeding Poland's largest power plant heeded a call today by Solidarity leaders and agreed to return to work.

headline: U. S. Reported Talking with Salvador Rebels
abstract: LEAD: A newspaper said today that State Department officials have held secret talks with guerrillas in El Salvador in an attempt to reach a negotiated settlement of the conflict in that country.

headline: Some Slight Signs Of a Cooling
abstract: LEAD: The statistics shifted enough last week to offset anxieties of inflation thatwere stoked the previous week by a report that wholesale prices had surged by 1 percent in February. This week's report on February's Consumer Price Index showed a rise of four-tenths of 1 percent - less than most analysts had predicted and lower than January's increase of six-tenths of 1 percent.

headline: U.S., in Shift, Asks Arbitration in World Court
abstract: LEAD: The United States will submit an international dispute for arbitration by the International Court of Justice in the Hague on Monday for the first time since President Reagan rejected the Court's jurisdiction in a quarrel with Nicaragua three years ago.

headline: Rates Rise Again in Credit Markets
abstract: LEAD: Interest rates continued to rise yesterday, but Treasury securities dealers said the rise was mostly related to the increase in the Federal funds rate, rather than to the half-point increase in the Federal Reserve's discount rate, to 7 percent.

headline: SOUTH KOREA CHIEF RENEGES ON PLEDGE FOR A REFERENDUM
abstract: LEAD: Warning of a ''repetition of confusion and violence'' in his country, the South Korean President, Roh Tae Woo, said today that he was indefinitely postponing a long-awaited referendum on his first year in office.

headline: HDTV Plea On Soviets
abstract: LEAD: A House subcommittee asked the Commerce Department yesterday to determine whether a planned demonstration of high-definition television equipment in the Soviet Union would result in the transfer of sensitive technology.

headline: U.S. May Ease Curbs on Oil Companies in Libya
abstract: LEAD: President Reagan is expected this week to lift some prohibitions on American oil companies doing business in Libya to prevent theirlosing their assets in the country, Administration officials said today.

headline: Avoiding Heat On Pay Increase
abstract: LEAD: The current dispute jover a pay raise for members of Congress is only the latest example of Washington's reliance on extra-constitutional mechanisms to protect elected officials from disapproving constituents. Scholars call it ''blame avoidance.''

headline: Bush Seen as Opposing Iran Arms
abstract: LEAD: At two White House meetings on the sale of American arms to Iran, in December 1985 and May 1986, George Bush supported Robert C. McFarlane's advice to Ronald Reagan that the operation should not proceed, according to a published interview with Mr. McFarlane.

headline: U.S. Agencies Asked for Landsat Aid
abstract: LEAD: The Federal agencies that make the most use of the data from the Landsat Earth-sensing satellites are being asked to contribute to keep the system operating after March 31, Thomas N. Pyke Jr. of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said today.

headline: Shipment of U.S. Chemical Seized on Way to Iran
abstract: LEAD: The Dutch police seized a large shipment of an American-made chemical used in rocket fuel that was bound for Iran last year, according to court documents and American officials.

headline: Appeal Due By Centaur
abstract: LEAD: Centaur Partners said today that it would appeal a judge's order blocking a special meeting of the Pennwalt Corporation's shareholders and said it was ''unwavering'' in its resolve to take over the chemical company.

headline: G.M. Saturn Dealers
abstract: LEAD: A group of 26 men Sunday became the first franchised dealers for the General Motors Corporation's Saturn subsidiary. The 26 dealers, based in large automobile-selling markets in 11 states, are the first of about 90 dealers who will begin selling Saturn cars in the fall of 1990, said Donald Hudler, Saturn's vice president for sales, service and marketing.

headline: Ads Decline in Wall St. Journal and Barron's
abstract: LEAD: Financial advertising at The Wall Street Journal and Barron's, the weekly business paper, continues to fall, even though the stock market has recovered somewhat from the October 1987 crash.

headline: 3d Man Charged as Insider
abstract: LEAD: The Securities and Exchange Commission yesterday accused a college classmate of a former analyst at Morgan Stanley & Company of illegal insider trading.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; G. Heileman Brewing Gets a New President
abstract: LEAD: Murray S. Cutbush, 43, an associate director of the Bond Corporation, has been appointed president and chief operating officer of the G. Heileman Brewing Company. He will succeed Russell G. Cleary, 55, Heileman's chairman, president and chief executive since 1971, who said Monday that he would retire.

headline: Bond Default Hearings Set
abstract: LEAD: Bondholders involved in the $2.25 billion default on two Washington state nuclear plants are being alerted today through notices in 14 newspapers that a Federal judge will hold hearings April 11 on whether a $750 million settlement is adequate and reasonable.

headline: A Record Year for Banks, But F.D.I.C.'s 'Worst Ever'
abstract: LEAD: Bank profits set a record in 1988, but for the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, which insures bank deposits, ''it was the worst year ever,'' L. William Seidman, chairman of the F.D.I.C., told analysts yesterday.

headline: Minkow of ZZZZ Best Gets 25 Years
abstract: LEAD: Barry Minkow, who as a teen-ager founded the ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning company, was sentenced today to 25 years in prison and ordered to pay $26 million restitution for fraud.

headline: Ryder Plans Unit Sales And Buyback of Stock
abstract: LEAD: Ryder System Inc. said today that it planned to buy back up to 15 percent of its common stock and that it was exploring the sale of its Insurance Management Services division and other operations.

headline: U.S. Warns Salvador on Rights Cases
abstract: LEAD: The recent collapse of a key human rights case and the failure to make progress in another have prompted renewed political controversy here and warnings that United States aid to this country could be cut.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  THE ECONOMY  In the first 20 days of February, net deposit outflows at the nation's savings and loan institutions were at a monthly rate of $5.2 billion, while in January the outflow was about $7 billion. Bank Board officials said the report reflected some regained confidence by consumers in the industry.

headline: Suit at U.S. Shoe
abstract: LEAD: Six shareholders of the United States Shoe Corporation have sued to block the planned sale of its footwear division to an investor group led by Merrill Lynch Capital Partners for $422.5 million. headline: Note Issue Sold By Massachusetts
abstract: LEAD: Massachusetts sold $490 million of notes through competitive bidding yesterday, with better than three-quarters of the financing going to Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. The remaining notes went to Morgan Stanley & Company and Bear, Stearns & Company.

headline: Fed Signals Another Rate Rise
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Reserve yesterday sent a strong signal that it has moved to push short-term interest rates still higher.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * American Capital Management and Research, Houston, a provider of financial services, to EBW Advertising, with a $2 million budget.

headline: High Court Plea on Detroit Papers
abstract: LEAD: Opponents of a partial merger of The Detroit News and The Detroit Free Press asked the Supreme Court today to delay completion of the business agreement so there will be further time for appeal.

headline: Formica Accords
abstract: LEAD: The Formica Corporation, which has agreed to be acquired in a management-led buyout for $18 a share, or about $230 million, said its financial adviser, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., had been reached by third parties interested in taking over the decorative-laminates concern. In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Formica, based in Wayne, N.J., said it had entered into confidentiality agreements with an unspecified number of the parties.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Commercial Cost Dispute Heats Up
abstract: LEAD: ANGER is still coursing through the commercial production industry, a month after a leading advertising agency executive contended that independent production companies were behind the rise in the cost of making television ads.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Official Named By the Four A's
abstract: LEAD: O. Burtch Drake, a seasoned manager with international experience, was named executive vice president and chief operating officer of the American Association of Advertising Agencies yesterday. Mr. Drake was most recently president of the European branch of Foote, Cone & Belding Communications.

headline: Destruction of Afghan Bridge Seen as Blow to Defense of Jalalabad
abstract: LEAD: Afghan Government efforts to defend the strategic city of Jalalabad appeared to have suffered a setback today with the disclosure that a key bridge had been blown up by Muslim guerrillas.

headline: This Actor-Politician Says It's Bedtime for Bases
abstract: LEAD: When Senator Joseph Estrada, a man with his eye on the presidency, was Mayor of San Juan, a suburb of Manila, the distinctions between his role in Government and his career as a popular movie tough guy sometimes blurred.

headline: British Merger Official Named Natwest Chief
abstract: LEAD: Lord Alexander of Weedon, chairman of the Panel on Takeovers and Mergers since 1987, has been appointed chairman of the National Westminster Bank P.L.C., Britain's biggest bank, effective Jan. 1.

headline: Detroit Papers' Merger Gains
abstract: LEAD: The full United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia said today that it would not hear a challenge to the merger of the business operations of Detroit's two daily newspapers.

headline: Restrictions Set On Gibraltar
abstract: LEAD: The Gibraltar Financial Corporation, a financially troubled savings institution, has entered an agreement with the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation that restricts the company's operations. Gibraltar, based in Beverly

headline: Motorola's Labor War
abstract: LEAD: The violence is over at Motorola Korea Ltd. - at least for now. There are no more workers dousing themselves with paint thinner, barricading themselves in the computer room and threatening to die for the right to form a union. But the fledgling union and management are no closer to agreement than before.

headline: Patents; A Crawling Machine, For Exercise
abstract: LEAD: Because of the interest in fitness, exercise buffs already have a wide range of machines that simulate running, rowing, bicycle riding and step-climbing.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Chick-Fil-A Account
abstract: LEAD: Chick-Fil-A, the Atlanta-based fast-food chain, ended a yearlong search for an advertising agency on Friday by appointing Frankenberry, Laughlin & Constable of Milwaukee to handle the creative portion of its account of about $6 million. The agency joins Rollheiser, Holland, Kahler of Omaha, which has been serving as Chick-Fil-A's promotions company for two years.

headline: U.S. Praises Salvador Chief's Plan As Best Chance to End Civil War
abstract: LEAD: The State Department today praised a peace proposal by President Jose Napoleon Duarte of El Salvador as ''potentially the most significant opportunity ever'' for a resolution of that country's nine-year-old civil war.

headline: Lear Joins With Columbia To Produce TV, Not Manage
abstract: LEAD: Norman Lear, creator of ''All in the Family'' and one of the most innovative producers of comedy shows in television history, said today that he would return to producing programs after a long hiatus.

headline: Article 157189 -- No Title
abstract: LEAD: The State of Florida entered the debt market yesterday with a $90.2 million competitive issue of general-obligation bonds. An underwriting group led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets successfully bid for the issue. For shorter maturities, investors are offered serial bonds priced to yield from 6.65 percent for an issue due in 1990 to 6.85 percent in 1994, 7.10 percent in 1999, 7.35 percent in 2004 and 7.45 percent in 2009.

headline: SALVADOR REBELS MAKE NEW OFFER
abstract: LEAD: Leftist guerrilla commanders agreed today to come here to talk about a peace initiative outlining conditions under which the rebels would take part in elections for the first time.

headline: Morrow's All-Out Push Helps Wambaugh Book to the Top
abstract: LEAD: When Joseph Wambaugh was ready to sell his latest book, a true crime account of a murder in England, he thought it had little chance of becoming a best seller. Uncertain that his longtime publisher would be enthusiastic, he considered turning to another publishing house for just that one book. But when Mr.

headline: DEBUNKING OF MAO: Li Shuxian, Professor, China
abstract: LEAD: Granddaughter of a wealthy landlord and daughter of a doctor who died when she was 5 years old, Li Shuxian, now 53, spent her youth in poverty. She welcomed the revolution and joined the party in 1954, only to be expelled three years later in an ''anti-rightist'' campaign and then, finally, reinstated automatically along with other purge victims in 1979.

headline: Hungary's Party Compromises on View of Uprising
abstract: LEAD: The Communist Party Central Committee today endorsed a compromise to end a leadership dispute over whether the 1956 Hungarian uprising, which was crushed by the Soviet Army, was a popular uprising or a counterrevolution.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; D'Arcy Masius Sells Office to DDB Needham
abstract: LEAD: D'Arcy Masius Benton & Bowles/ U.S.A. announced the sale yesterday of its San Francisco office to DDB Needham. No terms were disclosed, but people involved in the deal said it was a non-cash transaction that included DDB Needham's assumption of D.M.B.&B.'s lease, and potential payments to D.M.B.&B.

abstract: LEAD:  Economic and Social Council  STATISTICAL COMMISSION - 10 A.M. and 3 P.M.

headline: Nissan in Venture
abstract: LEAD: The Structural Dynamics Research Corporation and the Nissan Motor Company, the big Japanese auto maker, have formed a joint company to provide engineering consulting services in the Far East. The joint venture marks the first time Nissan has teamed up with an overseas company to begin a new business activity.

headline: CONTINENTAL AIR'S PRESIDENT QUITS
abstract: LEAD: Martin R. Shugrue resigned as president of Continental Airlines yesterday, the carrier's second top executive in a year and a half to fall victim to the tough management style created by Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of the Texas Air Corporation, Continental's corporate parent.

headline: Cuba's 30 Castro Years: Pluses, Minus the Gaiety
abstract: LEAD: Thirty years ago today Cubans poured into the streets of Havana, cheering and honking car horns, to celebrate the collapse of a brutal dictatorship and the promise of a better way of life.

headline: Dali's Gift to Spain: No Homage to Catalonia
abstract: LEAD: Salvador Dali's last joke is reverberating across Spain, sowing the kind of consternation and dissension that the Surrealist master succeeded in creating so successfully in his lifetime.

headline: Rover Group Chairman Taking Cadbury Post
abstract: LEAD: After 14 years as chairman of Cadbury Schweppes P.L.C., Sir Adrian Cadbury is stepping down. Sir Adrian, who will be 60 in April, the normal retirement age for directors, will formally take his leave after the annual meeting in May. He will be succeeded by Sir Graham Day, chairman of Rover Group P.L.C.

headline: Ouster Of Milken Seen Near
abstract: LEAD: Michael R. Milken, the head of the high-yield bond unit at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., will be removed from the firm and receive virtually none of his pay for last year as part of Drexel's settlement with the Government of charges of securities law violations, people familiar with the agreement said late yesterday.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  EASTERN'S BANKRUPTCY  Eastern Airlines filed for bankruptcy protection in an attempt to conserve cash and to gain time to persuade striking employees to return to work. Meanwhile, Eastern continued to operate limited flights.  [ Page A1. ]  Thousands of Eastern ticket holders, confused and angry, turned travel agents' offices into chaos.

headline: German Inflation 2.5%
abstract: LEAD: West Germany's average annual inflation rate rose sharply in January, to 2.5 percent, its highest level in three and a half years, preliminary figures showed today.

headline: Treasury Prices Rise in Quiet Day
abstract: LEAD: A drop in oil prices and another strong advance by the dollar helped lift prices of Treasury notes and bonds yesterday. Market participants said trading was a bit more brisk than in Monday's session but remained quite light.

headline: Pacific Resources Head Calls Deal 'Imaginative'
abstract: LEAD: For Robert G. Reed 3d, the chairman, president and chief executive of Pacific Resources Inc., the proposed acquisition of his Hawaii-based company by a large Australian crude producer is a ''win-win deal for everybody.''

headline: The New, Revealing Look of Taiwan Elections
abstract: LEAD: Elections used to be simple things here. The ruling party would nominate candidates who would win elections, and candidates would wear clothes.

headline: Dispute Seen as Threat to Arms Talks
abstract: LEAD: A last-minute dispute between Greece and Turkey threatens the completion of an East-West agreement that would open the way to new talks on reducing conventional forces in Europe, State Department officials said today.

headline: Bookstores Look to Instant Ordering
abstract: LEAD: Customers who order an out-of-stock title from a bookstore would be well advised to settle down with another book while awaiting delivery -something on the order of ''War and Peace.'' While book publishing has modernized some production methods, the process of getting books from the warehouse remains mired in antiquity.

headline: Retirement Plans
abstract: LEAD: Because of the changes wrought by the 1986 tax act, William H. Sterling and his wife, Marion, can no longer deduct the $4,000 they contribute each year to individual retirement accounts.

headline: Los Angeles Bonds' Top Yield Is 7.45%
abstract: LEAD: A refunding of about $206 million of securities by the Los Angeles Department of Airports through competitive bid offers a maximum yield of about 7.45 percent for an issue due in 2010. The underwriters are led by the First Boston Corporation.

headline: First Interstate Sees Losses at Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Texas unit of First Interstate Bancorp will continue to lose money this year, the company's chairman, Joseph J. Pinola, said. Asked whether losses at Allied Bancshares Inc. of Houston would approach the $199.7 million shortfall as of November, Mr. Pinola said: ''Of course not.''

abstract: LEAD: Following are excerpts from the Pentagon briefing today on the downing of the two Libyan jets, including the opening statement by Defense Secretary Frank C. headline: London Journal; 'Pygmalion' Updated: Henry Higgins Was Right
abstract: LEAD: John Honey is a kind of real-life, latter-day Henry Higgins, urging his countrymen to acknowledge that speech accents are lethal weapons in the English class war and to strike a blow for social equality by teaching everyone to speak the Queen's English.

headline: The Next Refrigerator May Take a Step Back
abstract: LEAD: In recent decades, refrigerators have gotten bigger, more stylish and - since the mid-1970's at least -more energy efficient as well. But a growing conflict between rules intended to improve the energy efficiency of appliances and measures to protect the earth's ozone layer may produce a new generation of more costly, less convenient refrigerators and freezers in the 1990's.

headline: Palestinian Is Killed In Protests in Gaza; Many Are Wounded
abstract: LEAD: A Palestinian in the occupied Gaza Strip was killed by soldiers today and dozens of others were wounded during widespread violent protests against the army's harsh new measures to quell the Palestinian uprising.

headline: Managua Acts to Revive Businesses
abstract: LEAD: Soliciting broad support for their new program of economic austerity, Sandinista leaders have declared that their top priority will be to revitalize the country's beleaguered private business sector.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * iBank One, Columbus, Columbus, Ohio, a unit of Banc One Corp., said Tod J. Ortlip, president and chief executive of Planned Communities Inc., had been elected to its board.

headline: Excerpts From Vatican's Declaration on Racism
abstract: LEAD: Following, in official translation, are excerpts from the Vatican document on racism issued today:

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Boeing Co., Seattle, saw its stock fall by $1.375, to $58.50, after announcing last week that it might be forced to delay deliveries of the latest version of its 747 aircraft.

headline: Navy Calls the Deployment Of a Carrier Group 'Routine'
abstract: LEAD: A 13-ship aircraft carrier battle group that left Norfolk, Va., on Friday for the Mediterranean was sent on a ''routine deployment,'' a Navy spokesman said today.
