headline: U.S. Team to Inspect Soviet Mental Hospitals
abstract: LEAD: A team of American experts will begin a long-awaited visit to Soviet mental hospitals next week to determine if political dissidents are still imprisoned there, American and Soviet officials said today.

headline: G.E. Unit Executive Named As Kidder, Peabody Chief
abstract: LEAD: The General Electric Capital Corporation, a financial subsidiary of the General Electric Company, announced yesterday that Michael A. Carpenter, an executive vice president, had been named president and chief executive of its Kidder, Peabody Group.

headline: Street Dramatist in India Slain Over Play
abstract: LEAD: A leftist who was one of India's most popular street theater directors was beaten to death by thugs last weekend after he refused a politician's demand to stop a drama in support of an opposing candidate, witnesses said.

headline: Garbage In . . .
abstract: LEAD: To the Editor:

headline: Salvador Political Parties Agree to Talk to Rebels
abstract: LEAD: Salvadoran political parties agreed in principle today to meet with leftist rebels to discuss a peace initiative that would lead to their participation in national elections.

headline: Fujitsu Unit Sets Venture
abstract: LEAD: A division of Fujitsu Microelectronics Inc. said today that it had formed a partnership with VIA Technologies Inc., an integrated circuit design company based in Fremont, Calif.

headline: Apple Offers New Computer
abstract: LEAD: Apple Computer Inc. introduced the Macintosh SE/30 today, a new computer that packs much of the power of the top-of-the-line Macintosh IIX into the smaller housing of the original Macintosh.

headline: Soviet Nuclear Ship Denied Entry at 4 Ports
abstract: LEAD: A Soviet nuclear-powered container ship has been denied entry at four ports in the Soviet Far East because of public protests, Soviet press reports said.

headline: Oil-Output Rise Asked
abstract: LEAD: Kuwait's oil minister, Sheik Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, was quoted today as saying that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries should raise its oil output ceiling by at least 8 percent, to 20 million barrels a day, in the second half of 1989. He told the Nicosia-based Middle East Economic Survey that ''in the second half, we ought to be talking of an increase of at least 1.5 million barrels per day.

headline: WHAT'S NEW IN MAGAZINE REDESIGN
abstract: LEAD: Magazine readers may have to search harder to spot their favorite title on the newsstand. Within the past year a number of well-known consumer and trade journals redesigned their styles and formats. The year 1988 marked the redesign of Ms. (February), Esquire (March), H.G.(March), Mademoiselle (May), Good Housekeeping (July), Glamour (July), Fortune (August) and most recently, Self (December) to name a few.

headline: Arabs, With Egypt in Forefront, Push U.S. Harder on Peace Talks
abstract: LEAD: With a series of meetings coinciding with the 10th anniversary today of Egypt's peace treaty with Israel, Arab leaders are seeking to draw the United States into a renewed effort to broaden the settlement and challenge the Israeli Government's rejection of the Palestine Liberation Organization.

headline: Johnson Unit Sues Amgen
abstract: LEAD: The Ortho Pharmaceutical Corporation, a division of Johnson & Johnson, filed suit today in Federal District Court in Delaware charging that Amgen Inc. has not honored the terms of a 1985 agreement between the companies regarding erythropoietin, or EPO, a hormone used to treat anemia.

headline: Coastal Extends Texas Eastern Bid
abstract: LEAD: The Coastal Corporation extended its $2.6 billion cash offer for the Texas Eastern Corporation by 10 days after the deadline for its original offer expired Monday. Coastal officials extended the $42-a-share offer to next Thursday, a spokesman, Robert Wells, said. Both companies are based in Houston.

headline: Pact for Development Bank
abstract: LEAD: Negotiators in Amsterdam reached agreement late tonight on the conditions for an infusion of $26 billion to the Inter-American Development Bank, a bank official said.

headline: Now, Novels Are Turning Promotional
abstract: LEAD: IT'S not as if Proust had traded his madeleines for pumpernickel in return for a payment from Pepperidge Farm, but Beth Ann Herman has raised hackles by putting her novel's protagonist in a Maserati.

headline: Armenia Prints Warning to K.G.B.; Called Fake
abstract: LEAD: An Armenian Communist Party newspaper has published what purports to be an anonymous ultimatum to the K.G.B., threatening to use American-made Stinger missiles in a campaign of ''mass terror'' if jailed Armenian nationalist leaders are not set free.

headline: Polaroid Stock Plan Upheld; Setback for Shamrock Seen
abstract: LEAD: The Delaware Chancery Court today determined that the Polaroid Corporation's employee stock ownership plan was valid, a ruling that appears to be a setback to Roy E. Disney's takeover bid for the film and camera company.

headline: Drilling for Oil Falling in U.S.; Price Rises Seen
abstract: LEAD: Faced with low oil prices and brighter drilling prospects abroad, oil and gas companies are continuing to cut spending on exploration in the United States.

headline: Moscow's Afghan Envoy Looks to Political Solution
abstract: LEAD: Moscow's special envoy to Afghanistan said today that the solution to the Afghan conflict lay in the political and not in the military realm.

headline: Spain's Banks Cautious After Failed Merger
abstract: LEAD: As two large Spanish banks picked up the pieces after their planned merger officially fell apart last week, bankers across the country began to consider the repercussions of the thwarted deal.

headline: Tyson Raises Bid For Holly Farms
abstract: LEAD: Tyson Foods Inc., the chicken processor that has pursued the Holly Farms Corporation since October, sweetened its tender offer to $63.50 a share, or $1.15 billion. In a letter to Holly's board, Tyson's chairman and chief executive, Don Tyson, raised the company's latest offer from $60 a share and conditioned it upon Holly ending a lock-up option with Conagra Inc., the

headline: Markets Chief Is Named In Freddie Mac Revamping
abstract: LEAD: Mark J. Latimer has been named to head a new capital markets group as a vice president of the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation, the Government-chartered organization known as Freddie Mac that provides a flow of funds to mortgage lenders.

headline: Chicago Inquiry, 2 Years Old, Still Has a Long Way to Go
abstract: LEAD: The Government's investigation of commodity trading continues to make headlines and to cast a pall over Chicago's financial district. But just where it will lead is far from clear.

headline: IRAN MAY BORROW AT BANKS ABROAD TO REVIVE ECONOMY
abstract: LEAD: On the 10th anniversary of its revolution, Iran has decided to borrow abroad for development projects and to resume exports of natural gas to the Soviet Union, Iran's oil minister said today.

headline: Ford Payments For Employees
abstract: LEAD: The Ford Motor Company said today that its 1988 profits would generate $460 million in profit-sharing payments, or more than $2,800 per employee, the second highest since the payments began six years ago.

headline: Networks Plan More Series Efforts
abstract: LEAD: ''Moonlighting,'' the ABC television show, has always tried to be a little different from other television shows by combining action, mystery, romance and comedy.

headline: Plane Order By Lufthansa
abstract: LEAD: Lufthansa German Airlines has agreed to buy up to 30 commerical aircraft from Airbus Industrie, a European consortium, in a deal worth an estimated $3 billion, Airbus officials said today.

headline: Early Exodus Portends Sudan Famine
abstract: LEAD: The ground here is scattered with freshly built straw huts and green tents, the makeshift shelters for the refugees who have started to leave the southern Sudan from fear of hunger.

headline: Profit Up 10.5% at Gannett; McGraw-Hill Posts Increase
abstract: LEAD: The Gannett Company said yesterday that its earnings rose 10.5 percent in the fourth quarter, while McGraw-Hill Inc. said its earnings improved by 10.2 percent.  Gannett

headline: Peru Optimistic After Big Oil Find
abstract: LEAD: The Occidental Petroleum Corporation has made a major oil discovery estimated at 600 million barrels that should convert Peru into a net exporter and guarantee supplies for 15 years, President Alan Garcia said.

headline: World Trade Spurted in '88
abstract: LEAD: World trade grew at its fastest rate in four years in 1988, the GATT trade body said today.

headline: Volcker Hails Fed Moves
abstract: LEAD: The former chairman of the Federal Reserve, Paul A. Volcker, today called inflation ''a perpetual concern'' and praised recent actions by the nation's central bank to nudge up interest rates to combat rising prices.

headline: Warning From Tokyo on Trade and Dollar
abstract: LEAD: A senior official of Japan's powerful Finance Ministry warned today that a widening trade surplus with the United States would not be improved by further declines in the dollar, suggesting that the Bush administration will have to take a markedly different approach to equalizing trade between the countries.

headline: Market Place; Growth Funds Post Biggest Gains
abstract: LEAD: In 1988, mutual fund investors who were willing to take risks generally did better than those who sought safety.

headline: Dow Slumps 29.64 More, To 2,262.50
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices yesterday continued the sharp slide that began on Friday in reaction to the report of a larger-than-expected rise in producer prices.

headline: Just Another Quick Fix?
abstract: LEAD: On the eve of the Presidential inauguration, members of the incoming Bush administration are reviving an old complaint about American businessmen: they concentrate too much on earning fast profits, sometimes wrecking their companies in the process.

headline: Your Money
abstract: LEAD: Some analysts think precious metals belong in everyone's portfolio, as a hedge against inflation, World War III or a particularly bad Super Bowl wager.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Campbell-Mithun-Esty's New York Chairman
abstract: LEAD: Campbell-Mithun-Esty yesterday named Richard Johnson as its New York chairman and chief creative officer. Since 1987, Mr. Johnson, 47 years old, has been the agency's Detroit president and chief creative officer and was a force in retaining the AMC/Jeep and Renault account for the agency and in building it to $150 million in billings.

headline: Japan's Trade Surplus Hit a Record Last Month
abstract: LEAD: Amid growing concern over its trade gap with the United States and Europe, Japanese officials reported today that the country's trade surplus had widened in December to $9.65 billion, a record monthly imbalance.

headline: Marcos in Honolulu Hospital
abstract: LEAD: Ferdinand E. Marcos, the former President of the Philippines, was in guarded condition with pneumonia after entering St. Francis Medical Center for the third time in little more than a month, a hospital spokeswoman said. Mr. Marcos, 71 years old, who is also suffering from bronchial asthma, returned to the hospital yesterday afternoon, said a nursing supervisor, Cindy Miller.

headline: Soviets, in Shift, Press for Accord In South Africa
abstract: LEAD: For 30 years until recently, the Soviet role in the South African conflict has primarily been that of principal supplier of the African National Congress, the principal armed black group fighting to overthrow white rule.

headline: I.R.S. Grace Period Satisfies Few Critics of Benefits Rule
abstract: LEAD: The Internal Revenue Service said today that the nation's three and a half million employers have until July 1 to begin complying with an ambitious new law covering benefit plans, and it said no penalties would be imposed this year so long as honest efforts to comply with the measure are made.

headline: Both Engines Apparently Failed On Airliner in Crash in England
abstract: LEAD: As the death toll rose to at least 44 in the crash of a British airliner in central England, Government investigators tried today to determine why both engines apparently failed on a three-month-old Boeing 737 jet.

headline: Rig Count Falls Again
abstract: LEAD: The number of working oil and natural gas rigs fell by 36, to 872, last week, Baker Hughes Inc. reported today. It was the second consecutive decline. The count dropped by 32 the week before. A year ago, the number of working rigs totaled 1,102. The count, a widely watched industry index of drilling activity, reflects the number of rigs exploring for oil.

headline: Stock Mutual Funds Regain Favor With Wary Investors
abstract: LEAD: Although investors have continued to be wary of most stock mutual funds, several funds with long-established records have experienced a burst of new business this year.

headline: Sri Lanka's President Appeals for an End to Political Killings
abstract: LEAD: President Ranasinghe Premadasa appealed today for an end to campaign-related violence that has killed hundreds of people and threatens Sri Lanka's first parliamentary elections in 11 years.

headline: Home Loan Banks Financing Set
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Home Loan Banks plan to announce the interest rates today for a five-part financing totaling $6.38 billion.

headline: Honeywell Venture
abstract: LEAD: Honeywell Inc. said Sterch, its joint venture with the Soviet Ministry of Mineral Fertilizer Production, had won three contracts in the Soviet Union worth a total of $8 million. Honeywell said the contracts cover the supply of process control systems and site services for modernizing ammonia fertilizer units at three chemical plants.

headline: F.D.I.C. Has No 'Magic' In the Savings Industry
abstract: LEAD: When the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation began taking control of insolvent savings and loan institutions on Tuesday as part of the Bush Administration's plan to solve the crisis in the industry, the Pacific Savings Bank of Costa Mesa, Calif., was as good a place to start as any.

headline: Marital Lapse by Australian
abstract: LEAD: Prime Minister Bob Hawke, dogged by questions about his personal life, tearfully admitted, in a television interview broadcast tonight, to being unfaithful to his wife of 33 years.

headline: Loan Credits to Bolivia
abstract: LEAD: The International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and Japan have approved credits for Bolivia totaling $93.3 million, the Finance Minister, Ramiro Cabezas, said on Tuesday. Mr. Cabezas said the I.M.F. had authorized the release of $35 million, the second stage of a $180 million loan to be disbursed over three years.

headline: France Seeks More Power For Its S.E.C.
abstract: LEAD: The French Government backed a legislative package today that would give greater enforcement powers to France's principal stock market watchdog, the Commission des Operations de Bourse, and would give companies new anti-takeover tools.

headline: 2-Year and 5-Year Notes to Be Auctioned
abstract: LEAD: The Treasury's schedule of new issues for this holiday-shortened week include today's regular weekly auction of three-month and six-month bills. New two-year notes will be auctioned tomorrow and five-year notes will be sold on Thursday.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Adia S.A., Zurich, the world's No. 2 temporary employment agency, expressed interest in buying ''substantial portions'' of Blue Arrow P.L.C., also an employment concern.

headline: West Germans Raid Spy Ring That Violated U.S. Computers
abstract: LEAD: The West German police said yesterday that they had broken up a major computer spy ring that worked with Soviet intelligence agents to steal United States military computer passwords, software and other data. Five people were arrested as investigators searched more than 15 houses and apartments in three cities.

headline: Summit in May Is Set by China And the Soviets
abstract: LEAD: China and the Soviet Union will hold a summit meeting in mid-May to achieve a ''complete normalization of relations,'' the Soviet Foreign Minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, announced here today.

headline: Power Agency's Revenue Bonds
abstract: LEAD: The Northern Municipal Power Agency, based in Minnesota, is tentatively offering a total of $302.8 million of electric-system revenue bonds to raise new money and retire previously issued debt in advance, with a maximum yield of 7.60 percent for an issue due in 2016.

headline: Stocks Finish Mixed; Dow Slips 1.25
abstract: LEAD: Stocks ended narrowly mixed yesterday after the market's early gains were erased by the continued weakness of blue-chip issues.

headline: New Saatchi Division
abstract: LEAD: Saatchi & Saatchi Promotions Inc., the promotions arm of the British-American conglomerate, said yesterday that it had formed a new division to generate promotional campaigns for entertainment and consumer product companies. The division will be called Saatchi & Saatchi Entertainment.

headline: Europe, Facing Tough Decisions, Now Cautious on a Single Market
abstract: LEAD: After an initial period of high excitement about the creation of a single market of 320 million consumers by the end of 1992, Western European politicians and citizens have started to register skeptical and even frightened accents as hard decisions loom on pivotal issues.

headline: About Real Estate; Waterfront Project in East Hampton
abstract: LEAD: The view from a 110-acre waterfront site under development at Northwest Harbor in East Hampton, L.I., is of a pristine landscape little changed since the town's earliest settlers, who came from Connecticut, landed here in the mid-17th century.

headline: Trade Arbitration Plan
abstract: LEAD: The European Community has given a cool response to a proposal made by a group of United States Congressmen to set up a bilateral panel to arbitrate trade disputes between the United States and the community. A spokesman for the European Community's External Relations Commissioner, Frans Andriessen, said Friday that the community was more interested in strengthening the procedures of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the Geneva-based international trade body.

headline: Addenda
abstract: LEAD: * Joseph K. Fisher, formerly chairman and chief executive officer of Fisher Jackson Levy Flaxman, has formed Fisher & Co., a marketing consulting firm whose specialty will be corporate and financial communications.

headline: Amer Group to Acquire Wilson Sporting Goods
abstract: LEAD: Amer Group Ltd., a diversified company based in Finland, said yesterday that it would acquire the Wilson Sporting Goods Company, the largest sporting goods maker in the United States.

headline: New Warwick Official
abstract: LEAD: Dennis Visich, an executive vice president and senior management representative at BBDO New York, is leaving to become the chief operating officer of Warwick Advertising. Wilder D. Baker, Warwick's president, has served as both the chief operating officer and chief executive for three years. But the growth of the agency, from $140 million to $160 million in billings last year, demanded an expansion of the top management ranks, Mr.

headline: Debt-Equity Swaps Draw Latin Criticisms
abstract: LEAD: As the incoming Bush administration prepares to take its promised new look at Latin America's foreign debt crisis, the one well-tried method of reducing the region's payments - through conversion of debt into equity - is coming under fire in several countries.

headline: FINANCE/NEW ISSUES;
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation, known as Freddie Mac, is offering to the public two issues of short-term notes totaling $1 billion with maturities of three and six months. The offerings are being made through Freddie Mac and an 18-member selling group. Both issues were priced at par.

headline: Manila Loan From I.M.F.
abstract: LEAD: The Philippine Finance Secretary, Vicente Jayme, said today that terms for a $1.3 billion loan from the International Monetary Fund would be submitted to President Corazon Aquino for approval this week.

headline: Appointee at Salomon Has Brash Reputation
abstract: LEAD: Lee H. Kimmell, 39 years old, who has been named to head the merchant banking efforts at Salomon Brothers, is a figure with a colorful reputation on Wall Street. He is viewed from inside and outside the firm as a smart investment banker who built Salomon's financial institutions advisory business into one of the most profitable areas of investment banking at the firm.

headline: Control Shifts At Insurer In France
abstract: LEAD: Bernard Pagezy, chairman of Compagnie du Midi, France's second-largest insurance company, lost out today to Claude Bebear, Midi's vice chairman, in a battle for control of the company.

headline: Sharp to Griffin Bacal
abstract: LEAD: Griffin Bacal has won the account for the Sharp Electronics Corporation of Mahwah, N.J., the American unit of the Sharp Corporation of Japan. The New Jersey operation, which makes consumer electronics and office automation products, has a budget for broadcast and print advertising of $12 million to $15 million.

headline: Starting Fast, Bush Phones Gorbachev
abstract: LEAD: On his first working day in office, President Bush moved quickly today to establish a personal dialogue with his foreign counterparts, including making a telephone call to Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet leader.

headline: Rising Stocks May Bolster Bonds
abstract: LEAD: The stock market, which has tended to take its cue from interest rates since the 1987 crash, may now be a major source of strength for the credit markets, some analysts contend.

headline: Carletonville Journal; 'Whites Only' Is One Thing the Blacks Won't Buy
abstract: LEAD: ''We are not living in the 1950's any longer. It is we blacks who have got the economic buying power now, and we can make the whites feel the pinch.''

headline: Dow Climbs Another 25.18; Nears 2,300
abstract: LEAD: Wall Street's 1989 rally continued unabated yesterday, with the Dow Jones industrial average gaining 25.18 points to close at 2,291.07, another post-crash high.

headline: U.S. and Allies Veto U.N. Move on Libyan Planes
abstract: LEAD: A resolution that deplored the downing of two Libyan fighter planes by American fighters over the Mediterranean last week was vetoed in the Security Council tonight by the United States, Britain and France.

headline: Ex-Official Defends Role on Eastern
abstract: LEAD: Former Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said Wednesday that an ethics official allowed him to rule in a case involving Eastern Airlines even though he was negotiating at the time for jobs with law firms linked to the company.

headline: FINANCE/NEW ISSUES;
abstract: LEAD: The Financing Corporation, an arm of the Federal Home Loan Bank system that raises money for the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation, priced $500 million of 30-year bonds yesterday through Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.

headline: Penney to Cease Teleaction Service
abstract: LEAD: J. C. Penney Inc. said it would discontinue its Teleaction television shopping service on April 7, taking a $20 million write-off and laying off 164 employees. The Dallas-based retailer said that it would take the accounting charge in the quarter ending April 29, adding that it had invested $106 million to develop the at-home shopping service.

headline: Rescue Promissory Notes Under Fire
abstract: LEAD: With savings and loan rescues coming under greater Congressional scrutiny, the $18 billion of promissory notes issued by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board to help sell off insolvent institutions have become a pawn in a fierce political debate.

headline: Deficit Cited by Northrop
abstract: LEAD: The Northrop Corporation said today that it lost $86.1 million in the fourth quarter after setting aside $150 million for possible losses on several classified military research and development projects.

headline: IN QUOTES
abstract: LEAD: ''Someone had to use the product for at least a week to get used to it, and that's an extraordinary requirement for a consumer. We live in the world of instant gratification.''   Lawrence Adelman, analyst at Dean, Witter on the smokeless cigarette.

headline: Court Refuses To Remove Drexel Judge
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Court of Appeals in New York has declined to review the matter of whether the presiding judge should be disqualified from a civil lawsuit brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission against Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and four of its employees.

headline: Moscow-Seoul Fish Ship
abstract: LEAD: South Korea and the Soviet Union, which have no diplomatic relations, said on Thursday that they would operate a fish factory ship in the first joint venture between the two countries. Kirill Levshov, director general of Sovinterinvest, told a news conference that a Soviet vessel, being repaired in South Korea, would go into operation next year.

headline: Now Anyone Can Play Violin
abstract: LEAD: A Silicon Valley company has come up with what it thinks is the answer for those who have the desire to play guitar like Eric Clapton but lack the talented fingers to do so - an electronic kazoo.

headline: Donations for Memorial To Philip H. Dougherty
abstract: LEAD: The Philip H. Dougherty Memorial Committee, an ad hoc advertising group, announced that it had received more than $50,000 in donations toward a memorial being established at Ithaca College in honor of the late advertising columnist of The New York Times.

headline: Texas Eastern, Coastal to Meet
abstract: LEAD: The Coastal Corporation, which has bid $2.6 billion for the Texas Eastern Corporation, said that a meeting between officials of the two companies has been arranged for this weekend. Coastal said it owns about 4 percent of Texas Eastern's outstanding common stock on a fully diluted basis.

headline: Patents; Carving a Line With an Electron Beam
abstract: LEAD: Alvin Marks, the founder of Phototherm Inc., in Amherst, N.H., has obtained patent approval for a new sub-micron beam writer, a device that carves lines far smaller than those in the circuitry of state-of-the-art computer chips.

abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Motorola, LSI Post Profits
abstract: LEAD: Belying reports of an electronics industry slowdown, Motorola Inc. reported on Friday record results for the fourth quarter and the year that ended on Dec. 31. The LSI Logic Corporation, meanwhile, reported lower earnings for the quarter but higher profits for the year.

headline: Baker Brings an Inner Circle Of Outsiders to State Dept.
abstract: LEAD: When the Soviet Foreign Minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, took his seat across the table from Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d at their first meeting in Vienna two weeks ago, he surveyed Mr. Baker's aides sitting to his left and right and then pronounced mischievously, ''I see that in the American delegation there are some new faces.

headline: IN QUOTES
abstract: LEAD: ''Peace is better than war. Why fight when they are doing the job I wanted to see done.'' - Carl C. Icahn, on his accord with Texaco.

headline: Europe Inflation Threat
abstract: LEAD: Rising inflation is threatening the European Community's brisk economic growth, the 12-nation bloc's Executive Commission said today. The community's economy is expected to grow by about 3 percent a year over the next two years, but the trend is at risk because of several factors, notably higher inflation, the commission said.

headline: South African Leader Has 'Mild Stroke'
abstract: LEAD: President P. W. Botha, South Africa's leader for the last 10 years, suffered a ''mild stroke'' early today, a presidential spokesman said.

headline: Massachusetts Sets Offering Of $430 Million in Bonds
abstract: LEAD: Massachusetts is tentatively offering $430 million in general obligation bonds with a maximum yield of about 7.55 percent for an issue due in 2007 through underwriters led by Goldman, Sachs & Company.

headline: Yields Post Weekly Gain
abstract: LEAD: Yields for certificates of deposit, bank money market accounts and money market mutual funds rose for the week ended yesterday. The increases were slightly larger than those reported the previous week.

headline: Banks Seen As Gaining In Rescue
abstract: LEAD: Commercial bankers may not want to gloat about it, but they may well turn out to be clear winners in the Government's rescue plan for the savings and loan industry.

headline: Boeing Gets $3.15 Billion Order for Jets
abstract: LEAD: A leading Japanese airline yesterday announced a $3.15 billion deal for 20 of Boeing's newest jumbo jets, the 747-400. The deal is the biggest purchase yet of the long-range, wide-body airplanes that are equipped with engines made by the General Electric Company.

headline: 12 Slain in Bombay In Anti-Rushdie Riot
abstract: LEAD: At least 12 people were killed and 40wounded when the police fired on Muslims rioting against ''The Satanic Verses'' in Bombay, birthplace of the novel's author, Salman Rushdie.

headline: American, Delta Plan Partnership
abstract: LEAD: In a bold move to strengthen their competitive positions, American Airlines and Delta Air Lines Inc. announced yesterday that they would form a partnership to operate a global computer reservation system.

headline: Chrysler Plant to Make A New Jeep
abstract: LEAD: Responding to growing consumer preference for sports-utility vehicles, the Chrysler Corporation said today that an assembly plant here would be transformed to produce a new-model Jeep.

headline: Gains Toward Cambodia Settlement Are Seen
abstract: LEAD: Diplomats and Thai officials say the necessary elements for a comprehensive settlement in Cambodia are rapidly coming together.

headline: Bauer Starts 2d Magazine For Women
abstract: LEAD: THE Bauer Group, a West German publishing company, clearly believes that once is not enough. Having already started Woman's World, a weekly magazine, Bauer has added a monthly, First for Women, to its American magazines.

headline: New Ventures Are Planned For 2 Koreas
abstract: LEAD: The founder of the Hyundai Corporation, Chung Ju Yung, announced plans today for several more joint ventures between North and South Korea amid some Government concern about the pace of economic cooperation.

headline: Liechtenstein Political Crisis
abstract: LEAD: The 15-member Parliament of this tiny Central European principality was dissolved today after a dispute between the two coalition parties.

headline: Dow Off 9.29, to 2,282.14, on Jobless Report
abstract: LEAD: The stock market retreated yesterday in the face of a Government report on employment that increased fears that the Federal Reserve may push up interest rates to curb inflationary pressures.

headline: Tibetans' Houses Raided by Chinese Troops
abstract: LEAD: Security forces dragged Tibetans from their houses today as thousands of Chinese troops took up posts around Lhasa today after three days of anti-Chinese riots, travelers said.

headline: Ships Lost in Atlantic Storm
abstract: LEAD: A fierce storm in the Atlantic Ocean sank or disabled eight ships, authorities said today. Eight people drowned, 25 were missing and presumed dead, and at least 80 people were saved, rescue workers said.

headline: 17 Lost as Freighter Sinks in Atlantic Storm
abstract: LEAD: All 17 seamen on a Panamanian-registered freighter were believed dead today after the ship sank in a North Atlantic storm northwest of Ireland.

headline: Toronto-Dominion $150 Million Issue
abstract: LEAD: The New York branch of the Toronto-Dominion Bank offered $150 milllion of 10-year subordinated notes.

headline: Elcetronic Gear Is Prized But Few Can Afford It
abstract: LEAD: Technology enables physically impaired people to hold jobs they otherwise could not. A computer equipped with an electronic voice will read back letters typed in by a visually impaired person for accuracy. Similarly, some computers will articulate words identified on the screen, enabling people with speech difficiencies to communicate.

headline: About Real Estate; Avoiding That Lookalike Syndrome
abstract: LEAD: The first homeowners association to be created in the town of Clarkstown in Rockland County is about half completed, and it has led to an unusual rule that gives the town a backup role in assuring that all such developments are properly maintained.

headline: Castro Foe Reports Trip to Havana And a Possible Thaw in Hostility
abstract: LEAD: For the first time in a decade, some of Miami's strongly anti-Castro Cuban exiles have begun an exchange of views with representatives of the Cuban Government.

headline: Iowa TV Station for Sale
abstract: LEAD: Iowa's first television station, KWQC-TV of Davenport, has been offered for sale by Palmer Communications Inc. William Ryan, president and chief executive of Palmer, a privately held communications company based in Des Moines, said this week that Palmer had hired Howard Stark, a New York television broker, to sell the station.

headline: Compromise on Leadership Reached by Retailers Group
abstract: LEAD: After a four-day convention marked by opposition between large retail members and small ones, the directors of the National Retail Merchants Association moved to smooth things over yesterday by appointing a small-store merchant as its new chairman and a big-store chief executive as first vice chairman.

headline: SWIM IN LAKE ERIE, SEE STORMS IN DULUTH
abstract: LEAD: The Great Lakes have only recently been recognized for their potential to trigger fresh business development. After all, it was only 20 years ago that Lake Erie, which had been suffocating from a lack of oxygen, was declared ecologically dead. The problems with water quality in the Great Lakes are far from solved.

headline: Lord & Taylor to Bolster Presence in New Jersey
abstract: LEAD: Lord & Taylor, the New York-based fashion chain that has been expanding rapidly around the nation in recent years, will soon have a stronger presence in New Jersey.

headline: 18 Lawyers Defecting From Shea & Gould
abstract: LEAD: Continuing its pattern of aggressive expansion, the law firm Myerson & Kuhn said yesterday that it would open a Los Angeles office with 18 lawyers who are defecting from Shea & Gould.

headline: Philip Morris Note Yield Is 10.526%
abstract: LEAD: The Philip Morris Companies is offering $300 million of 10 1/2 percent notes due 1990 at a price of 99.75 to yield 10.526 percent through Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.

headline: New York Perspectives
abstract: LEAD: The School of Visual Arts in Manhattan will showcase the work of its illustration students at New York Landscapes, an exhibition that opens tomorrow at the Art Directors Club. The illustrators have envisioned New York from non-human perspectives, showing the city from a roach's- and poodle's-eye view, among other vantage points.

headline: Dalai Lama Sees a Culture Endangered
abstract: LEAD: Fearful of both hard-liners in the Chinese leadership and young Tibetans eager to challenge Beijing with violence, the Dalai Lama appealed today to China, his own followers and the West to help save Tibetan culture from annihilation.

headline: Electronic Filing Speeds Refunds
abstract: LEAD: Once every 15 minutes the smiling face of Bob Mirsberger, Manhattan director of the I.R.S., flashes on an electric color billboard over Times Square with an enthusiasic exhortation to ''Make Your Taxes Less Taxing By Filing Early & Electronically.'' This year, some two million taxpayers will take that advice to heart by having their tax data sent by computer and modem as part of the Internal Revenue Service's electronic filing program.

headline: East Europe's Burden of Debt
abstract: LEAD: The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development warned today that the increasing debt of Eastern Europe could cause payments problems if world interest rates continued to rise.

headline: Abercrombie & Fitch Chief Sees Growth Opportunities
abstract: LEAD: Sally Frame-Kasaks yesterday was named the president and chief executive of Abercrombie & Fitch, the fashion and sports apparel chain owned by the Limited Inc. Mrs. Kasaks, 44, was previously the president of Talbots Inc., the classic New England apparel retailer, and before that the president of the Ann Taylor Inc.

headline: Rebuild America by Rebuilding Labor
abstract: LEAD: A dangerous, virtually unquestioned assumption has taken hold of American management - that the best way to be competitive is to cut people, wages and salaries. This assumption has led to the trade deficits that are bankrupting America, and it is making our nation dependent on foreign powers for all manner of capital, products and - increasingly - technology.

headline: 21 Reported Killed in Yugoslavia In Ethnic Albanian Disturbances
abstract: LEAD: At least 21 people have been killed in the last two days in rioting by ethnic Albanians in the Kosovo region, the authorities said today. The Albanians have been protesting legislative changes that will curb the autonomy of the predominantly Albanian region.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; People
abstract: LEAD: * Susan M. Machtiger has been named senior vice president at Young & Rubicam New York.

headline: PROTESTS FOLLOW HANGING OF 2 SIKHS
abstract: LEAD: Stores and schools in predominantly Sikh areas were closed today to protest the hanging of two Sikhs for the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi.

headline: Anti-U.S. Protesters in Seoul Battle With Police for Hours
abstract: LEAD: South Korean riot policemen fought running battles with thousands of club-wielding anti-American demonstrators trying to storm the parliament building in Seoul today, witnesses said.

headline: Real Estate; Pre-Retirement Homes In Jersey Grow Fancier
abstract: LEAD: When pre-retirement condominiums were first being developed 20 years ago on the farmlands of central New Jersey, the emphasis was on simple one-bedroom, one-bath ranch houses no larger than 900 square feet. Now, as new units are added to these developments, they are becoming communities of decidedly more elaborate dwellings.

headline: ROUND OF SELLING ENDS DOLLAR RALLY
abstract: LEAD: A new, coordinated round of dollar selling by central banks, led by the Federal Reserve and the West German Bundesbank, stopped a new year's rally in the dollar yesterday.

headline: Lagos Journal; Once a Month, an Unruly City Scrapes Itself Clean
abstract: LEAD: There used to be an axiom among seasoned travelers about Lagos, black Africa's most populous city: the reality is even worse than the horror stories.

headline: State Taxes Stir a Fight
abstract: LEAD: Residents of New York City still have the unenviable distinction of paying the highest combined Federal, state and local tax rates in the nation - 41 percent for those in the 33 percent Federal bracket and 36.6 percent for those in the 28 percent Federal bracket.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; A Mad Parody Of Adweek
abstract: LEAD: Employees at ad agencies in Los Angeles blinked on Monday when they picked up their familiar trade magazine - the one with the bright red masthead.

headline: Lithuania Nationalists: A Fine and Fragile Line
abstract: LEAD: Ignoring damp snowflakes, Lithuanians by the thousands filed into the sylvan amphitheater of a Vilnius park the other day for an election rally.

headline: Globex Plan Supported
abstract: LEAD: The staff of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission officially recommended today that the agency approve Globex, a computerized trading system proposed by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. It would allow its futures or options contracts to be traded away from the traditional trading pit.

headline: Dow Up 4.82 Points in Moderate Trading
abstract: LEAD: Stock prices were mixed yesterday, as blue chips staged a modest rally even as the broader market weakened.

headline: Price Data Put Dow Back on the Plus Side
abstract: LEAD: After the stock market's steepest two-day slide since August, stock prices rose modestly yesterday, buoyed by a smaller-than-expected rise of four-tenths of 1 percent in the Consumer Price Index for February.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Happy Times In Linkups, And in Splits
abstract: LEAD: THE only advertising executives happier than those who have recently sold their agencies to larger partners appear to be those who have just bought themselves back from their corporate parents.

headline: Commodities Exchange Seeks Advice
abstract: LEAD: The Chicago Board of Trade announced today that it had hired a former assistant United States attorney to advise it and its members on the use of Federal racketeering laws in white-collar crime cases.

headline: After Years in Shadow of the U.S., Soviets Take the Mideast Initiative
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union's first major Middle East initiative in years gathered momentum today with word that Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze is to meet separately with both the Israeli Foreign Minister and the chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization this week to discuss revived proposals for peace.

headline: Soundings From East and West: Faith in the Face of Upheaval; A Sense of Rectitude: Mario Benedetti, Auto mechanic, Italy
abstract: LEAD: An auto mechanic for more than 30 years, Mario Benedetti, 54, has a garage next to a big gas station where he employs his son and one other mechanic. He is a painter and an avid reader, and he has been active in Italy's Communist Party since his youth. No one else in his family has joined the party - proof, he says, of the freedom of choice that Communists allow.

headline: Gorbachev Asks Stable Relations
abstract: LEAD: Mikhail S. Gorbachev congratulated President Bush and expressed hope for stable relations.

headline: Wheat Offer Made to China
abstract: LEAD: The United States Agriculture Department on Friday offered to subsidize sales of one million metric tons of wheat to China, the second such offer this month.

headline: Bush Aides' Plan on Savings Units Is Said to Place Cost on Industry
abstract: LEAD: The Treasury plans to submit proposals to President Bush on Saturday that will place much of the burden for dealing with the savings and loan crisis on private industry, Congressional aides and industry experts said today.

headline: Marriott in Venture With Soviet Airline
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet airline Aeroflot and the Marriott Corporation announced a venture to supply about 10,000 meals a day to Aeroflot passengers. The catering operation would be the first in the Soviet Union to involve a Western concern, the companies said.

headline: Qaddafi Denies Role In Sabotage of Plane
abstract: LEAD: The Libyan leader, Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, said today that he believes that sabotage caused the explosion and crash of a Pan Am jet in Scotland, but he denied that either his country, Iran or Syria had a role in it.

headline: CNN in Latin America
abstract: LEAD: The Turner Broadcasting System said today that it would transmit the Cable News Network 24 hours a day to Latin America on the Pan American Satellite Corporation's international satellite. The agreement followed tests that began in November, TBS said. Turner's decision to use Pan American Satellite is a victory for the private company, based in Greenwich, Conn., and a defeat for Intelsat, the international consortium that operates most communications satellites.

headline: Prague Court Reduce Playwright's Sentence
abstract: LEAD: An appeals court today reduced the jail sentence of the playwright Vaclav Havel from nine months to eight and reduced one of two charges against the dissident.

headline: Market Holiday
abstract: LEAD: Stock, bond and futures markets are closed today in observance of Presidents' Day. Government offices and most banks are also closed, as are many businesses.

headline: Business and the Law; Foreign Lawyers Migrating to U.S.
abstract: LEAD: EAGER to follow the rapidly growing United States investments of their clients, foreign lawyers are beginning to flock to American shores. And economic and regulatory forces are encouraging the trend.

headline: Conference Is Planned On Retail Ad Strategies
abstract: LEAD: The Retail Marketing Society will sponsor a special conference on retail advertising strategies on March 22. The conference, to be held at the New York Hilton, will include lunch-time remarks by Jerry Della Femina, the irrepressible chairman of Della Femina, McNamee WCRS, who will answer the question, ''Is retail advertising real advertising?

headline: Deal Set by McDonnell And General Dynamics
abstract: LEAD: Five weeks after receiving a huge order for its wide-bodied MD-11 commercial aircraft, the McDonnell Douglas Corporation said today that it had agreed to pay the General Dynamics Corporation about $2 billion over the next six years to produce fuselage sections for the new plane.

headline: Greek Cypriots Seek Accord
abstract: LEAD: President George Vassiliou of Cyprus said today that the country's Greek Cypriots were ready to make major concessions to Turkish Cypriots to end the Mediterranean island's 14-year division. President Vassiliou, speaking at the Royal Institute of International Affairs in London, also called on Western European countries to help reunite Cyprus and achieve withdrawal of 29,000 Turkish troops estimated to be in the north.

headline: Allegheny Spurns Compromise Plan
abstract: LEAD: The board of Allegheny International Inc. voted late yesterday to reject a compromise plan of reorganization that was supported by the company's creditors. The plan would have allowed Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Inc. to buy Allegheny in exchange for selling its profitable patio furniture and outdoor grill units to an investor group led by Paul S.

headline: Bush, Building on Old Ties, Is Scheduled to Arrive in Beijing
abstract: LEAD: Seven years ago, during a difficult period in Chinese-American relations, George Bush visited China and sat down at a table with Deng Xiaoping, the senior Chinese leader, and many officials on each side.

headline: Market Place; Milder Rise Seen For 1989 Profits
abstract: LEAD: WITH a lower dollar prompting stronger exports for many companies and years of restructurings in basic industries helping to cut costs, corporate profits in 1988 rose far more rapidly than expected when the year began.

headline: Market Place; Tax Angle Is Key To Texaco Accord
abstract: LEAD: A BASIC rule of investing is that a dollar now is better than a dollar later. But Texaco Inc.'s settlement with Carl C. Icahn specifies delayed payouts in a way that will benefit some stockholders - Mr. Icahn in particular - while doing little to aid either individual or institutional investors.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  THE ECONOMY  Inflation is unacceptably high, Alan Greenspan said, raising the possibility of higher short-term rates. The markets responded favorably to his anti-inflation stance. [ Page A1. ] Criminal charges against Drexel Burnham Lambert were filed by the Government. The details indicate a broader range of illegal activities than had been disclosed.

headline: Montazeri, Khomeini's Designated Successor in Iran, Quits Under Pressure
abstract: LEAD: In the most striking rearrangement of Iran's theocratic leadership since the revolution 10 years ago, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini has ousted his designated heir apparent, Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri.

headline: Reporter's Notebook; Neither Mud Nor Lost Divinity Mars Emperor's Rites
abstract: LEAD: By the time that Emperor Hirohito's funeral procession wound its way through Tokyo's gray streets this morning, Shinjuku Gyoen was already a sea of mud.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Alaska Air Group Inc., Seattle, said its Alaska Airlines unit would purchase six additional MD-80 aircraft from McDonnell Douglas Corp. in addition to a previous order for seven other MD-80 aircraft. The two orders represent a commitment of approximately $390 million.

headline: First Interstate's Turn to Squirm
abstract: LEAD: A little more than two years ago, Joseph J. Pinola, chairman and chief executive of the First Interstate Bancorp, made an audacious bid to buy the BankAmerica Corporation. BankAmerica was more than twice First Interstate's size, but it was in shambles - its stock was depressed, its capital base weak and its management surprised by a series of loan losses and other misfortunes.

headline: SOVIET VOTERS DEAL HUMILIATING BLOW TO PARTY OFFICIALS
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet electorate has dealt a mortifying rebuke to the high and mighty in elections for a new national congress, including stunning upsets of a Politburo member and several other senior Communist Party officials who ran without opposition.

headline: Limited Net Rises 89.7%
abstract: LEAD: The Limited Inc., the nation's largest women's apparel retailer, today reported a surge in fourth-quarter profit.

headline: Treasury Prices Dip in Hectic Day
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds moved lower yesterday in a hectic session dominated by concerns about the dollar and news that Congress might ask the Treasury to issue $50 billion worth of bonds before Sept. 30 to deal with the savings and loan crisis.

headline: '88 Inflation Up, I.M.F. Reports
abstract: LEAD: The inflation rate in industrial nations rose in 1988 for the second consecutive year, the International Monetary Fund said in a report released this week.

headline: ETHNIC RUSSIANS MARCH IN ESTONIA
abstract: LEAD: Thousands of Russians and other non-Estonians marched in Tallinn today, threatening a general strike if the Communist Party does not stem Estonian nationalism and ''creeping counterrevolution,'' journalists there said.

headline: Farm Export Forecast
abstract: LEAD: Both the value and tonnage of United States farm exports are recovering at a faster pace than expected three months ago, the Agriculture Department said on Thursday. The report said the department had increased its estimate for agricultural exports in the 1989 fiscal year to $38 billion and to 145 million metric tons, a rise of 8 percent in export values from $35.3 billion in the 1988 fiscal year that ended Sept.

headline: No Utopia, but to Workers It's a Job
abstract: LEAD: In the four years since a shuttered General Motors Corporation factory here re-opened as a joint venture with the Toyota Motors Corporation, the resurrected assembly plant has been hailed as proof that a labor and management utopia could be created in American heavy industry.

headline: Market Place; A Highflier of '88 Is Lagging in '89
abstract: LEAD: THERE are few things nicer in life than a monopoly in a rapidly growing market, which is the main reason that Wall Street fell in love with Adobe Systems Inc., a Silicon Valley company whose principal product is an integral part of desktop publishing systems.

headline: Dow Chemical Sees Record 1989 Sales
abstract: LEAD: The Dow Chemical Company said it expects to achieve record sales again in 1989 and predicts it will nearly double its revenues to $30 billion a year by the mid-1990's. In the company's annual report to shareholders, Dow's president, Frank Popoff, said the Midland, Mich., company expects to exceed the record $16.7 billion in sales it posted in 1988.

headline: EX-AIDES CRITICIZE RUMANIA'S LEADER
abstract: LEAD: Six former officials of the Rumanian Communist Party have sent a letter to President Nicolae Ceausescu attacking the Rumanian leader's hard-line policies, Western diplomats and Eastern bloc journalists in Bucharest said today.

headline: To Our Readers
abstract: LEAD: Because of computer problems at The Associated Press, today's Options on Futures table does not include figures for sales and open interest.

headline: Sony's Profits Up 44.4%
abstract: LEAD: The Sony Corporation said today that its earnings rose 44.4 percent in its third quarter on healthy sales gains. The company's profits in the period ended Dec. 31 totaled 28.9 billion yen, or $229 million, up from 20 billion yen a year earlier. Sales totaled 613.8 billion yen, or $4.87 billion, an increase of 36.8 percent from 448.7 billion yen.

abstract: LEAD:  The Economy

headline: U.N. Approves Namibia Plan
abstract: LEAD: The Security Council unanimously approved a resolution today to carry out an independence plan for Namibia.

headline: Battle Over a Blood-Clotting Protein Is Avoided
abstract: LEAD: Two biotechnology companies and their marketing partners announced a worldwide cross-licensing agreement yesterday for genetically engineered Factor VIII, a blood-clotting protein that 40,000 hemophiliacs rely on to prevent painful and often fatal bleeding.

headline: Chinese Dissident Freed From Jail, but Restricted
abstract: LEAD: A campaigner for democracy who had studied in the United States was released from a Chinese prison today. But a Government official said he would not be able to return to America for at least a year.

headline: Money Fund Assets Up

abstract: LEAD: The Justice Department plans to examine closely the proposed merger of computerized airline reservation systems operated by Delta Air Lines Inc. and American Airlines Inc.

headline: Durable Goods Orders Dropped 3% in January
abstract: LEAD: Orders to factories for ''big ticket'' durable goods dropped 3 percent in January, the Commerce Department said today. Some analysts said the report could portend a welcome slowdown in economic growth.

The former Philippine leader, who was indicted last October, is in a hospital in Honolulu, where, his lawyers say, he is being treated for pneumonia, asthmatic bronchitis and a heart ailment.

headline: Kabul Uses Heavy Missiles on Rebels

headline: India Paper's Investment Bothers Rival Publishers

abstract: LEAD: The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation took control of 45 insolvent savings and loan associations with assets of $13.6 billion today, bringing to 118 the number of sick institutions that it has seized in accord with President Bush's savings bailout plan.

abstract: LEAD: In a major blow to United States policy in this country, municipal government has collapsed in many rural areas.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * Bell Canada Enterprises Inc., Montreal, said its BCE Development Corp. unit and Olympia & York Developments Ltd. have ended talks on the acquisition by Olympia & York of an interest in BCE Development.

headline: German Press and Foes Attack Kohl Over Libya
abstract: LEAD: Chancellor Helmut Kohl came under strong attack from the political opposition and the press today over his Government's disclosure that it had known since October of potential West German involvment in the construction of a suspect Libyan chemical factory.

headline: Italian Bank Under Inquiry
abstract: LEAD: Sixteen senior bankers, one of them a Cabinet minister, have been told they are being investigated about irregularities in the balance sheets of an Italian merchant bank, judicial officials said on Saturday.

headline: Addenda
abstract: LEAD: * The American Advertising Federation has issued a call for nominations for its third annual Distinguished Advertising Educator Award. For information and nomination forms, call (202) 898-0089.

headline: Prices Paid to Farmers Rise 0.7% in Month
abstract: LEAD: The prices that farmers received for raw products rose seven-tenths of 1 percent from February to March, averaging 15 percent more than a year ago, the Agriculture Department said today.

headline: Whittle Chief Executive Announces Resignation
abstract: LEAD: Nicholas Glover, president and chief executive of Whittle Communications, announced his resignation yesterday after five years at the Knoxville, Tenn., publishing partnership he helped to build. Time Inc. bought a 50 percent interest in the company last month for $185 million, with provisions to increase its stake over the next five years.

headline: Construction Spending Up In December
abstract: LEAD: Construction spending rose 2.5 percent in December, ending the year on a strong note, the Commerce Department reported today.

headline: Brady Adds to Savings Numbers: $24 Billion for Closings in the 90's
abstract: LEAD: Less than three weeks after the Bush Administration announced a $90 billion rescue plan for the savings industry, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady said today that the Government would have to spend an additional $24 billion to shut savings and loan associations that become insolvent in the 1990's.

headline: 10 Boeing Jets Ordered by U.P.S.
abstract: LEAD: United Parcel Service Inc. has ordered 10 more Boeing 757-200PF jet freighters at a cost of about $500 million, the aircraft maker said today. In 1985, U.P.S., based in Greenwich, Conn., ordered 20 of the 757-200PF's - for ''package freighters'' - and took options on 15 more. Today's order converts 10 of those options into firm sales.

headline: BUSINESS DIGEST
abstract: LEAD:  THE ECONOMY  President Bush's savings-industry rescue plan is based on assumptions that interest rates will decline sharply and deposits will increase steadily, according to figures from the Office of Management and Budget. Some analysts criticized the projections as being too optimistic.

headline: Maxwell May Delay Paper
abstract: LEAD: The British publisher Robert Maxwell canceled an important address Friday about the introduction of his English-language newspaper, The European, saying his editorial team was not yet ''pursuing shared goals and a unified concept.''

headline: U.S. Believes Some Contras Abused Prisoners
abstract: LEAD: Bush Administration officials said today that they had tentatively concluded that some of the Nicaraguan guerrillas tortured prisoners and committed other human rights abuses in their camps in Honduras.

headline: Auto Sales Fell 14.8% in Early March
abstract: LEAD: Domestic automobile sales declined 14.8 percent in the first 10 days of March, despite higher buyer incentives. Analysts predicted that the decline would lead to further discounting and perhaps a cut in production to clear excess inventories.

headline: THE MEN BEHIND THE BIGGEST STORIES ON WALL STREET AND IN WASHINGTON: HENRY R. KRAVIS, Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts; RJR Nabisco Deal A Triumphant Work For Master of Buyouts
abstract: LEAD: The buyout specialist Henry R. Kravis began last year by donating $10 million to build the Henry R. Kravis wing at the Metropolitan Museum of Art and followed with $10 million for the Mount Sinai Medical Center.

headline: Sony Seeks TV Grant From U.S.
abstract: LEAD: In a development that could lead to widespread debate over Government sponsorship of foreign research efforts, the Sony Corporation of America said yesterday that it had submitted a bid to the Defense Department for contracts to develop a high-definition television system.

headline: As Oakland Rises, Its Paper Endures
abstract: LEAD: Robert C. Maynard, the owner, president and editor of The Tribune, has spent nearly six years trying to cut costs, woo advertisers and improve the long-struggling newspaper.

headline: Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Orangina USA, a soft-drink maker whose parent is Austin Nichols & Co., a subsidiary of Pernod-Ricard S.A., Paris, to Angotti, Thomas, Hedge, with a budget of more than $2 million.

headline: Debate Grows on Development Fees
abstract: LEAD: Local governments are increasingly demanding that real estate developers pay for everything from road improvements to day-care centers, a practice that is driving prices of new homes higher in some regions and intensifying the debate over whether such charges amount to an unfair tax on new residents.

headline: Market Place; If Closed Funds Go Open-Ended
abstract: LEAD: WHEN it comes to closed-end funds, Wall Street seems to think that what happens to one fund in a group will not affect the rest.

headline: Japan Confirms Extension of Its Car Quotas
abstract: LEAD: The Japanese Government confirmed today that it would continue its ''voluntary'' restraints on automobile exports for another year.

headline: Syrian-Soviet Meetings Said to Be Stepping Up
abstract: LEAD: Syria and the Soviet Union will increase political and military consultations to head off a possible split as Moscow increases its diplomatic efforts in the Middle East, Arab diplomats say.

headline: Problems Beset Two Years of Talks
abstract: LEAD: Time Warner Inc. is coming into the world like an elephant, two years in gestation and a giant at birth. The path from conception to delivery was fraught with problems, including conflicts between the parents about who would bear the most responsibility for the upbringing.

headline: Fed Implies Wait-and-See View on Rates
abstract: LEAD: Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, indicated today that the central bank had adopted a wait-and-see approach toward further increases in interest rates to keep inflation under control.

headline: National Lampoon Board Expanded
abstract: LEAD: Matty Simmons, the chairman of National Lampoon Inc., has agreed to expand the company's board to seven seats from four and to add as directors the actor Tim Matheson, who played Otter in ''Animal House''; David Grodnik, a motion picture and television producer, and an Omaha investor, Alan S. Parsow.

headline: Edelman Increases Storehouse Stake
abstract: LEAD: Storehouse P.L.C. said Asher B. Edelman, the American takeover specialist, had raised his stake in the British retailing group to 7 percent from 6.1 percent. Mr. Edelman notified Storehouse that he had increased his holdings to 28.8 million shares, continuing the slow stake building begun late last year, the company said.

headline: Forecast: No Recession
abstract: LEAD: Although the Federal Reserve Board's tighter monetary policy has apparently slowed economic growth, the economy is not about to fall into a recession, a University of Michigan forecast said today. The economist Saul Hymans, director of the university's Research Seminar in Quantitative Economics, forecast a 4 percent annual growth rate in the first quarter.

headline: SALVADOR RIGHTIST WINS PRESIDENCY, BIG PARTIES AGREE
abstract: LEAD: The major political parties today declared Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Nationalist Republican Alliance the winner of the Salvadoran election, paving the way for him to succeed Jose Napoleon Duarte as president on June 1.

abstract: LEAD: Leaders of rival Christian and Muslim Cabinets have agreed to cooperate with the Arab League in an effort to prevent the formal partition of Lebanon, officials reported today.

Sallie Mae is a federally chartered stockholder-owned corporation that has financed about 4 in 10 of all guaranteed student loans outstanding today, Offered at a price of par, the notes are yielding a variable rate equal to 55-hundredths of a percentage point more than the bond-equivalent yield of the 91-day Treasury bill auction rate.

abstract: LEAD: CRITICS of dual trading, in which traders sometimes act for customers and sometimes for themselves, had better not hold their breath until the practice is abandoned. The decision by directors of the Chicago Board of Trade not to ban the practice is but one indication of how deeply ingrained it is at the nation's largest futures market.

headline: Missouri Offering Revenue Bonds

headline: Louisiana Bank Fails
abstract: LEAD: The Louisiana Bank and Trust Company of Shreveport, La., was closed and its deposits transferred to the Hibernia National Bank of New Orleans, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation said on Thursday. The failed bank had $272 million in assets, and the F.D.I.C. said it had advanced $99.6 million to facilitate the transaction.

headline: F.C.C. Licensing Plan
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Communications Commission today proposed putting into place a lottery system to award licenses for new AM and FM radio stations and for television stations. The system would replace its comparative hearings, in which applicants argue their qualifications. The commission said that the hearing process was too long, complex and expensive and that it had been a drain on the agency's administrative resources.

headline: Mid-Month Vehicle Sales Increase 2%
abstract: LEAD: Sales of new domestic cars and light trucks rose by 2 percent in mid-February over the comparable period last year, but analysts said the improvement was still not good enough to clear inventories and avert a discounting war.

headline: U.S. IS QUESTIONING ARAFAT'S CONTROL
abstract: LEAD: The United States today questioned the commitment of Yasir Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, to renounce terrorism and control radical Palestinian factions that have attempted incursions into Israel.

headline: Baker Balks at Dutch Request That He Undertake Mideast Mission
abstract: LEAD: The Dutch Foreign Minister called on Secretary of State James A. Baker 3d today to undertake a Middle East peace mission as early as possible, a senior American official said. But Mr. Baker responded that the conditions in the area were not yet ripe for an initiative.

headline: Increase in Precious Metals Follows Late Rally in Gold
abstract: LEAD: Precious metals closed higher yesterday after gold prices rebounded from a two-year intraday low.

headline: Mexico Inflation Down
abstract: LEAD: A wage and price freeze reduced inflation last year to 51.7 percent, down two-thirds from the 1987 rate, Mexico's central bank said on Monday. The Bank of Mexico noted that consumer prices rose by 159.2 percent in 1987. Last Feb. 29, the Government froze the peso's exchange rate against the dollar.

abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds fell in very sluggish trading yesterday, as market participants took profits following last week's strong rally and assumed a defensive stance in advance of a slew of upcoming economic and political developments later in the week.

It is the electronic still video camera, a device that looks like a bulky 35-millimeter camera but captures images on electronic sensors instead of film. The images are then stored on built-in magnetic disks that can be played back with a machine connected to a TV.

Although industry experts acknowledged the possibility that another suitor could emerge, most believe that the chances of that happening are small.

headline: Belgian-Zairian Links Eroding
abstract: LEAD: Relations between Belgium and Zaire, its former colony, have fallen to a new low with Zaire's announcement last weekend that the African country was scrapping cooperation agreements and suspending payments on the part of its $7 billion debt owed in Belgium.

abstract: LEAD: Pakistan has acquired from a West German company a plant for purifying a gas than can be used in nuclear weapons, a German prosecutor says.

headline: Uncovered Short Sales Are Off 0.2% on Big Board
abstract: LEAD: The New York Stock Exchange reported yesterday that short interest on the Big Board declined two-tenths of 1 percent in the four-week period ended March 15.

abstract: LEAD: A Soviet military commander acknowledged today that his country's forces are leaving Afghanistan with something of a sense of failure. He also denied that the Soviets have resumed their pullout but said they still plan to be out of the country by Feb. 15.

It would be the first business venture between the Soviet Union and South Korea. Jindo officials said their company, which produces 400,000 fur garments a year, signed a contract on Tuesday in Moscow with Interlink of the Soviet Union to set up the venture with an initial investment of $800,000.

headline: An Ex-Belgian Premier Is Believed Kidnapped

abstract: LEAD: TF Investments Inc., the management group that is seeking to acquire the Hospital Corporation of America in a $3.6 billion leveraged buyout, will have to sell certain assets to repay a $1.3 billion bridge loan within two years after the completion of the buyout.

abstract: LEAD: The Federal Trade Commission charged the Campbell Soup Company yesterday with deceptive advertising that contended its soups could reduce ''the risk of heart disease'' while not disclosing what the commission considers a high sodium content in the products.

abstract: LEAD: Several left-wing members of Parliament along with leaders of the Peace Now movement will take part in a symposium in New York this weekend that will also be attended by members of the Palestine Liberation Organization.

headline: Economic Scene; Why It Pays To Be Generous
abstract: LEAD: PRESIDENT BUSH'S inaugural call ''to celebrate the quieter, deeper successes that are not made of gold and silk'' probably will not persuade many free enterprisers to trade their Adam Smith neckties for ladles at the local soup kitchen. For Smith, after all, the glory of competitive markets lay in their capacity to direct private greed to public benefit.

headline: Conference on Penny Stocks
abstract: LEAD: The Securities and Exchange Commission's New York regional office held a one-day conference of 45 state, Federal and securities industry enforcement officials on Thursday as part of its effort to combat penny-stock fraud in the New York City area.

abstract: LEAD: India announced today that it would withdraw about 2,000 troops from Sri Lanka in the next few days, and officials said further troop reductions would follow.

abstract: LEAD: Merrill Lynch & Company, led by record earnings in its investment banking and trading divisions, yesterday reported sharp increases in earnings and revenues for the fourth quarter and the full year.

headline: At Bush's Beijing Villa, Marxists Pursue Profit
abstract: LEAD: As President Bush visits here this weekend, his lodgings will be testimony to China's growing interest in market economics.

abstract: LEAD: Interest rates declined at Citicorp's weekly auction of 91-day and 182-day commercial paper yesterday. It was only the second time this year that rates fell; the first was in early March.

abstract: LEAD: IN a bold assault on the $900 million market for birth control pills, a small Texas drug company began advertising its product directly to consumers this month.

headline: Mark Producing Sells Its Assets
abstract: LEAD: The Consolidated Natural Gas Company said it and a Japanese partner had agreed to acquire the exploration and production assets of Mark Producing Inc. for about $245 million in cash. Mark Producing, a Houston-based company, has extensive natural gas and oil properties in the Gulf of Mexico. The deal includes proven and probable reserves of 190 billion cubic feet of natural gas and five million barrels of oil.

headline: Mexican Union Chief Is King To the Oil Workers at Home
abstract: LEAD: In this drab industrial city on the Gulf Coast, the main supermarkets are owned by the Mexican oil workers union. So is the only funeral home and so are some of the auto repair shops and gasoline stations.

headline: California Utility In Bond Offering
abstract: LEAD: The Southern California Edison Company, a subsidiary of SCEcorp, is offering $150 million of first- and refunding-mortgage bonds due in 2020 through underwriters led by Salomon Brothers Inc., which made the winning bid in competition yesterday.

headline: Combat Pay in Gulf May End
abstract: LEAD: The general in charge of the United States Central Command has recommended suspension of combat pay for sailors in the Persian Gulf, Pentagon officials say. The recommendation, under review by the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is the strongest indication yet that American defense officials believe the truce between Iran and Iraq may hold.

headline: Kollmorgen Seeks Alternatives to Bid
abstract: LEAD: The Kollmorgen Corporation said it was in talks with third parties to discuss possible alternatives to the $294 million hostile tender offer from the Vernitron Corporation. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Kollmorgen said it had furnished financial information to the parties, but the Stamford, Conn., electrical machinery concern emphasized that it had made no decision to sell the company.

headline: Rates Are Mixed At Citicorp Auction
abstract: LEAD: Interest rates were mixed yesterday at Citicorp's weekly auction of 91-day and 182-day commercial paper. The bank holding company sold $50 million of 91-day paper at an average rate of 8.952 percent, down from 9.0393 percent last week and down for the second consecutive week.

headline: Offer to Brazil By World Bank
abstract: LEAD: The World Bank has offered Brazil a credit of $1 billion in the next 18 months for the power sector, the Brazilian Government said today.

headline: 15,000 Foes of Sandinistas March in Nicaragua
abstract: LEAD: A crowd of 15,000 chanting, cheering protesters marched through Managua today to dramatize their grievances against the Nicaraguan Government in the broadest collection of opposition groups since the Sandinista Front took power in 1979.

headline: President's Successor Is Chosen at Raytheon
abstract: LEAD: The Raytheon Company, the electronics company that had $8.2 billion in sales last year, has named Dennis J. Picard, 56 years old, as its next president.

headline: Angola Gives Hints of Willingness To Seek Political Solution to War
abstract: LEAD: In a sharp break with past policy, Angolan officials now indicate that they will seek a political solution to their nation's long-running civil war.

headline: Terrorism Alert: A System Shows Gaps
abstract: LEAD: The furor over whether the British authorities failed to pass along warnings about a new kind of terrorist bomb in time to prevent the destruction of a Pan Am jumbo jet has revealed a serious lack of coordination between governments and airlines on terrorism, diplomats and officials here say.

headline: Ford Plant Switch
abstract: LEAD: The Ford Motor Company said it would switch production of its Sierra model from Britain to Belgium as part of its strategy to prepare for a single European market at the end of 1992. The gradual production switch is likely to eliminate 500 jobs in Britain and create 2,000 jobs in Belgium, Ford said.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Toshiba Corp., Tokyo, to Calet, Hirsch & Spector, New York, for its corporate advertising, with a budget of more than $1 million.

headline: Scripps Sells Florida Paper
abstract: LEAD: The E. W. Scripps Company announced Friday that it had completed the sale of The Sun-Tattler, a newspaper in Hollywood, Fla., to DTH Media Inc., which owns The Dallas Times Herald. Terms were not disclosed.

headline: Pepsico in Sale Pact
abstract: LEAD: The General Cinema Corporation signed a definitive agreement for the previously announced $1.75 billion sale of its soft-drink bottling business to Pepsico Inc. The company said the transaction remained subject to clearance by the Federal Trade Commission under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Refinements In Corporate Sponsorship
abstract: LEAD: AS the sponsorship of traditional sporting events has grown more costly and crowded, companies like Reebok, K Mart and Chiquita Brands are turning to out-of-the-ordinary events to help polish their images and increase their sales.

headline: Korea Surplus With U.S. Dips
abstract: LEAD: The national trade surplus with the United States in the first 11 months of this year decreased to $7.61 billion, down $890 million from a year ago, the Korea Foreign Trade Association reported Friday. Under American pressure, Korea has eased import curbs and taken other steps in efforts to reduce the trade excess.

headline: Why Growth Stocks Could Soon Surge
abstract: LEAD: President Bush's proposal to cut the tax rate for capital gains faces an uphill battle in Congress. But investment experts say if such a cut were enacted the big winners would be the stocks of young companies whose earnings are growing rapidly but which pay out very little in dividends. Even without a tax cut, however, many Wall Street professionals believe that such stocks currently represent some of the best bargains around.

headline: Clouds on Credit Union Horizon
abstract: LEAD: While the savings industry has suffered $100 billion in losses on speculative real estate, fraud and mismanagement, and the banking industry has seen failures surge to more than 200 last year, one segment of the nation's financial sector seems to have known only bright days and clear skies in recent years.

headline: Soviet Writers, and Government, Avoid Public Outcry on Rushdie
abstract: LEAD: The predicament of the novelist Salman Rushdie, condemned to death by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomenei for his ''Satanic Verses,'' has a certain historical resonance in the land of Stalin.

headline: Amoco's Damages Raised By $30 Million in Cadiz Spill
abstract: LEAD: A Federal district judge in Chicago recommended yesterday that the Amoco Corporation pay about $115 million to France and nearly 90 French citizens and businesses that suffered damage from the huge oil spill of the Amoco Cadiz supertanker in 1978.

headline: Savings Unit Sales Backed
abstract: LEAD: The chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation said today that United States banks should be allowed to buy troubled savings and loan associations immediately without the customary restrictions imposed by the Federal Reserve Board.

abstract: LEAD: MacLean Hunter Ltd. said Friday that it had agreed to sell a television station in Hamilton, Ontario, to the Blackburn Group for about $57.4 million, or $68.5 million Canadian. MacLean Hunter said the station, CHCH-TV, had belonged to Selkirk Communications Ltd., which MacLean Hunter acquired earlier this month.

headline: U.S. Again Reports Libyan Role in Terrorism

headline: Your Money; Picking a Broker: How to Cut Risks

abstract: LEAD: A State Department official said Monday that the United States would give a Palestinian political figure, Faisal al-Husseini, a visa to come to the United States for a Middle East conference at Columbia University in New York from March 11 to 13.

headline: Fighting for a Place on Crowded Newsstands

headline: Economic Scene; Costa Rica's Debt Message
abstract: LEAD: AS goes Costa Rica's economy, so goes Latin America's? Fears of setting a precedent for the Latin mega-debtors - Mexico, Brazil, Argentina, Venezuela - have stopped foreign banks from settling accounts on realistic terms with this tiny nation. But now Costa Rica's sophisticated financial negotiators have turned the tables on their commercial creditors.

headline: Dollar Finishes Day Mixed After Intervention Abroad
abstract: LEAD: The dollar closed narrowly mixed yesterday against the major foreign currencies. Exchange dealers said trading slowed in New York after central banks in Europe intervened earlier to slow the dollar's rise.

abstract: LEAD: Classics Illustrated, the comic books that millions of schoolchildren read as introductions to and often substitutes for the world's great literature, will soon be available to another generation of students.
