Brown Group gained 50 cents, to $34.75, on the New York Stock Exchange. Late Friday, Brown Group said it would take an $18 million charge against earnings to cover losses on the sale of three specialty retailing businesses.

headline: China Gives the Dates For Gorbachev's Visit
abstract: LEAD: China said today that Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the Soviet leader, would visit here from May 15 to May 18 for the first Chinese-Soviet summit meeting in 30 years.

headline: Soviets, Delighted to Survive, Tolerate the Afghan Hoopla
abstract: LEAD: The Soviet Union marked the final stage of its withdrawal from Afghanistan with a show for the press today in this dusty border city.

headline: Honduran Who Promoted U.S. Aid to Contras Is Slain
abstract: LEAD: The former armed forces chief who closely cooperated with Washington in supporting the Nicaraguan rebel movement in Honduras was assassinated today by six men who riddled his car with gunfire, officials said.

headline: Chase Manhattan Cuts London Unit
abstract: LEAD: Chase Manhattan Equities, the British brokerage subsidiary of the Chase Manhattan Corporation, said it would withdraw from some London share trading operations and eliminate 135 jobs here. Chase said the trading volume and profits were too small, so it would withdraw from making markets in British equities.

headline: U.S.-Japan Fighter Deal
abstract: LEAD: After meetings between American officials and an envoy from Japan, officials of the two nations said today that both sides were considering their positions on changes the United States is seeking in a pact reached last year to build an advanced fighter plane.

headline: Hungarian Calls the East Bloc a Crisis Zone
abstract: LEAD: A member of the Hungarian leadership, Imre Pozsgay, has described Eastern Europe as the world's largest crisis zone.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; P.&G. to Pay Its Agencies More Money
abstract: LEAD: PROCTER & GAMBLE, the nation's second-largest advertiser and one of advertising's most influential forces, has informed its agencies that it is increasing the amount it will pay them to handle its advertising.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Big Accounts to Trone
abstract: LEAD: Trone Advertising, an agency based in Greensboro, N.C., has received nearly $6 million in billings from two major accounts in the last two weeks. Carlyle & Company, a jewelry store chain, awarded its $3.3 million account to Trone this week, and the Weyerhaeuser Company assigned a $2.5 million account last week.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD:  Debt

headline: Dollar Up Steeply in Europe; Trading Light in New York
abstract: LEAD: The dollar rose sharply in Europe yesterday and held its gains in light holiday trading in New York.

headline: COMPANY BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * American City Business Journals Inc., Kansas City, Mo., said its board had rejected a $15-a-share offer made last month by TA Associates Communications.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * American Tobacco Co., Stamford, Conn., promoted Vivian A. Parks Jr., Donald S. Johnston and Robert E. Sprinkle 3d to senior vice president and Thomas P. Kriz to controller.

headline: Bassett Foods To Fight Proposal
abstract: LEAD: The British maker of jellybabies, a popular gelatin candy, has vowed to fight a hostile takeover offer of $:63 million, about $112 million, from the Swedish company Procordia A.B. Bev Stokes, the chief executive of Bassett Foods P.L.C., said the offer by Procordia, Sweden's 10th-largest business, badly undervalued the company.

headline: Iran Rebuffs Britain on Rushdie's Novel
abstract: LEAD: Iran today rejected conciliatory comments by Britain's Foreign Secretary in the dispute over the novel ''The Satanic Verses,'' dismissing the remarks as ''playing with words.''

headline: 16 Die in Philippines
abstract: LEAD: A motor launch carrying more than 140 people sank in the central Philippines and at least 16 people were killed, the coast guard said today. Twelve people were reported missing. The vessel, the Jem II, sank Tuesday off Romblon Island, about 150 miles southeast of Manila, a coast guard officer said.

headline: Transit Account Seen For Ephron, Raboy
abstract: LEAD: After a month-long review, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority has reportedly called on Ephron, Raboy & Tsao Advertising to handle its advertising. The budget is expected to be in the $5 million range.

headline: Market Place; Bullish Approach To Savings Units
abstract: LEAD: With all the tumult over the nation's savings and loan industry, many investors might think it a good time to sell the stock of savings institutions. They might be wrong. While the Bush Administration's $90 billion plan to rescue the savings industry may blur the distinctions between savings associations and commercial banks, some experts believe that well-run savings institutions will prosper.

headline: Rights Group Reports Continued Abuses in Cuba
abstract: LEAD: A human rights organization based in New York said today that while Cuba has improved its prisons and permitted some dissident groups to form, it continues to commit ''serious violations of human rights that victimize the whole Cuban population.''

headline: Duarte Fears Vote Could Finally Lead To a Rebel Triumph
abstract: LEAD: With elections a few days away, President Jose Napoleon Duarte today warned of growing polarization and economic chaos that could lead to a rebel victory in El Salvador.

headline: U.N. Units Arrive in Namibia To Check Transition Process
abstract: LEAD: Finnish and Danish officers have arrived to make preparations for the arrival of other United Nations peacekeepers assigned to monitor Namibia's transition to independence.

headline: EXECUTIVE CHANGES
abstract: LEAD: * Comfed Bancorp Inc., Lowell, Mass., a bank holding company, said Gerald Schuster had resigned as vice chairman.

headline: Hewlett's Unit In South Africa
abstract: LEAD: The Hewlett-Packard Company said today that it would sell its South African sales subsidiary to Siltek Ltd., a South African manufacturer and distributor of computer products.

headline: C.D. and Money Market Yields Go Higher
abstract: LEAD: Yields for certificates of deposit and bank money market accounts continued to show strong gains for the week ended yesterday.

headline: Nissan Price Rise
abstract: LEAD: The Nissan Motor Corporation said it would raise the price of its two-door Pathfinder models by an average of $1,500 effective Monday in response to a recent Treasury Department ruling that the vehicle was intended primarily for commercial use and was therefore subject to a 25 percent import duty.

headline: Health-Care Company Gets 2 Plans
abstract: LEAD: American Medical International Inc. said today that it had received a buyout proposal valued at $1.7 billion from a group including its largest individual shareholder and that it was also considering a separate restructuring plan.

headline: Jaffna Journal; If the War Has Ended, Why Are So Many Dying?
abstract: LEAD: The arid Jaffna Peninsula, the center of Sri Lankan Tamil culture and once the seat of independent Tamil kings, is living under foreign military occupation, breeding new tensions to replace those that brought the soldiers here.

headline: Rates Expected to Remain Steady
abstract: LEAD: Barring sudden weakness in the dollar, credit market analysts predicted that interest rates should remain in a fairly narrow range for the next week or so. The next real test, they believe, will not come until mid-February, when the Treasury will hold its quarterly refunding auctions.

headline: SALVADOR VICTOR URGES PEACE TALKS
abstract: LEAD: President-elect Alfredo Cristiani called Tuesday for immediate negotiations with revolutionary guerrillas and asked the United States not to prejudge him or his party.

headline: In New Era, Banks May Avoid Blue-Chip Bonds
abstract: LEAD: As banking companies expand into the corporate bond market for the first time in more than 50 years, they are expected to avoid some low-profit sectors like bonds of blue-chip companies and concentrate on more lucrative financings involving lower-quality companies and new sectors of the market.

headline: Delaware Adds to Court
abstract: LEAD: A rising tide of corporate takeover battles has prompted Delaware to enlarge its Chancery Court, one of the nation's most important arbiters of corporate takeovers.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; New England Monthly to Be Sold
abstract: LEAD: New England Monthly, an award-winning magazine and one of the most prominent new consumer publications of the last five years, is being sold to Telemedia Inc., Canada's largest publisher of consumer magazines.

headline: Washington Expects a Tax Bill, but a Minor One
abstract: LEAD: There will be a tax bill this year, but it is unlikely to involve any major overhaul of the tax code or substantial new tax increases. So goes the prevailing wisdom among tax policy makers and lobbyists as the Bush Administration and Congress take their first tentative steps toward negotiation on the budget for the 1990 fiscal year.

headline: Venezuela Bars Oil as Collateral
abstract: LEAD: Venezuela's talks with banks on a $600 million bridge loan have stalled, the nation says, because it refuses to use oil as collateral.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; People
abstract: LEAD: * Richard A. Sukkar has been named chief financial officer of Earle Palmer Brown.

headline: Sudan Agrees to Discuss Emergency Famine Aid
abstract: LEAD: The Sudanese Government has invited representatives of United Nations relief agencies and other humanitarian organizations to Khartoum next month to discuss emergency steps to avert mass famine this spring, officials say.

headline: New Swap Plan By Freddie Mac
abstract: LEAD: The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation yesterday announced the introduction of a weighted-average-coupon adjustable-rate mortgage guarantor program. Under the program, Freddie Mac will swap its weighted-average-coupon adjustable-rate mortgage participation certificates for a like amount of adjustable-rate mortgages issued by lenders.

headline: Careers; A Good Side To Unwanted Job Changes
abstract: LEAD: AN outplacement expert, a management consultant and a management recruiter have some encouraging words for middle managers who have lost their jobs: maybe they will be better off changing jobs.

headline: THE MEDIA BUSINESS: Advertising; Prospering by Selling to the Prosperous
abstract: LEAD: THE arrival today of Robin Raj, the award-winning Chiat/Day copywriter, at Doyle Graf Mabley will mean a change of name for the five-year-old New York agency but not a shift in specialty - marketing to the wealthy and the would-be wealthy.

headline: Treasury Notes and Bonds Rise
abstract: LEAD: Prices of Treasury notes and bonds were generally higher in erratic trading yesterday.

headline: 'Junk Bond' Revolution Will Outlive Its Creator
abstract: LEAD: With his indictment on securities fraud charges, Michael R. Milken will no longer dictate the fate of companies from the helm of his ''junk bond'' empire in Beverly Hills, Calif., and he will have to leave Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the securities firm he helped build into a Wall Street powerhouse.

headline: Shamrock Extends Its Bid for Polaroid
abstract: LEAD: Shamrock Holdings Inc., the investor group controlled by Roy E. Disney that has sought the Polaroid Corporation since July, extended its $2.95 billion hostile bid for the photography giant for two months. Shamrock, based in Burbank, Calif., is offering $45 a share in cash for all of Polaroid's common stock, including the preferred shares associated with the company's shareholder rights plan.

headline: Lasmo Oil Deal
abstract: LEAD: The British oil company Lasmo said it would buy International Thomson Organization Ltd.'s British North Sea interests for $:358 million, or $623 million. Lasmo, formally called the London and Scottish Marine Oil P.L.C., is one of Britain's largest independent oil and gas exploration companies. It said the purchase of Thomson North Sea Holdings from Canada-based Thomson would almost double its North Sea production to 49,000 barrels of oil equivalent a day.

headline: Greenspan Defends Lifting Rates
abstract: LEAD: By raising interest rates substantially in the last 10 months, the Federal Reserve helped extend the nation's long economic expansion, Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, said today.

headline: American Is President Of Matsushita in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: The Matsushita Electric Corporation of America, the parent of Panasonic, Technics and Quasar, yesterday announced the appointment of Richard A. Kraft as president and chief operating officer, the first American to hold the posts.

headline: Centel Selling 2 Cable Groups
abstract: LEAD: The Centel Corporation said today that it and its Centel Cable Television Company subsidiary had reached definitive agreements to sell two more cable television operations, in Kentucky and Florida. Terms were not disclosed. These agreements are part of a plan announced last week to sell Centel Cable's properties in six groups.

headline: Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * 3M Corp. to Chiat/Day Advertising, San Francisco, for Scotchguard brands.

headline: Texas Instruments Plans Plant in Italy
abstract: LEAD: Texas Instruments said it would build a $250 million semiconductor fabrication plant in Avezzano, Italy, about 65 miles east of Rome, to supply the European semiconductor market. The plant will begin production of integrated circuit wafers, including dynamic random-access memory chips, in late 1990.

headline: Unisys Expects a Loss For the First Quarter
abstract: LEAD: The Unisys Corporation said yesterday that it expects to report a loss in the first quarter because of slower sales of its mainframe computers in the United States.

headline: Road to a New Debt Policy: Fed-Treasury Tug-of-War
abstract: LEAD: The Government's shift toward a more benevolent treatment of the developing world's debtors is unlikely to go as far as the Bush Administration wanted because of opposition from the Federal Reserve, people involved in the plans and other officials say.

headline: Polaroid Payout Plan Helps It Reach Shamrock Accord
abstract: LEAD: Agreeing to pass on to shareholders a sizable chunk of any damages it receives from the Eastman Kodak Company for patent infringement, the Polaroid Corporation yesterday reached a peace pact with Shamrock Holdings Inc., which has been trying to take it over since last summer.

headline: Sudan Agrees to Food Relief but Skepticism Persists
abstract: LEAD: Under increasing international pressure, the Sudanese Government says it has agreed to large-scale deliveries of relief food intended to avert a repetition of the hundreds of thousands of deaths from starvation that occurred last year.

headline: G.M. Planning Solar Car Race
abstract: LEAD: The General Motors Corporation said today that it would sponsor a solar-powered car race from Florida to Michigan next year for college and university teams and that it had received about 60 design proposals.

Change        1988   From '87       Coastal Corp.   $ 71,100,000    +102.9        Colgate-Palmolive Co.   126,700,000    +229.9        Culbro Corp.   (3,100,000)    -       B. F. Goodrich Co.   37,200,000    +81.5        Halliburton Co.   11,800,000    -65.4        Itel Corp.   200,000     *-       Norton Co.

headline: Group to Meet On Beef Issue
abstract: LEAD: A group of United States and European Community officials who will try to settle a trans-Atlantic trade dispute over hormones in beef will meet here Monday and Tuesday, United States officials said Friday.

headline: Construction Spending Rose 0.8% in November
abstract: LEAD: Construction spending rose eight-tenths of 1 percent in November, reflecting an increase in work on homes and government projects that more than offset slower building of offices and shopping malls, the Commerce Department reported today.

headline: Khomeini Is Well, Daughter Says
abstract: LEAD: Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the 88-year-old Iranian leader, is ''in good health,'' works hard and sometimes performs marriage ceremonies, his daughter says.

headline: A.T.& T. Says Annual Loss, Its First, Was $1.67 Billion
abstract: LEAD: The American Telephone and Telegraph Company yesterday reported, as expected, the first annual loss in its 104 years in business.

headline: As Brazil Vote Approaches, Magic of Democracy Wanes
abstract: LEAD: Five years ago this month, as Brazilians by the millions marched, shouted and danced in favor of direct presidential elections, democracy was proclaimed to be the cure for all the ills bequeathed by the departing military regime.

headline: GTE Income Off 2.4% in Quarter
abstract: LEAD: The GTE Corporation said yesterday that its net income in the fourth quarter declined 2.4 percent, to $326 million, or 96 cents a share, from $334 million, or 99 cents a share, in the comparable 1987 period. Revenues rose to $4.3 billion from $4.1 billion a year ago.

headline: Britain Agrees to Review the Case Of 4 Convicted of Bombings in '75
abstract: LEAD: The Court of Appeal will review the case of four accused guerrillas who were convicted in 1975 of the bombings of English bars, the British Government announced today. Seven people were killed in the bombings.

headline: About Real Estate; Queens Firehouse to Be Converted
abstract: LEAD: During its 40 years as a firehouse, the building at 89-56 162d Street in Jamaica, Queens, was known as ''the big house'' because of its size. The building, which occupies a 95-foot-by-73-foot site just north of Jamaica Avenue, was home to a ladder company and three engine companies, and served as a battalion headquarters until it was closed in 1965.

headline: Embattled Soviet Islamic Leader Quits Post
abstract: LEAD: The Islamic leader of Soviet Central Asia resigned today in the face of a highly unusual public challenge from critics who accused him of failing to live up to strict Muslim discipline.

headline: BUSINESS PEOPLE; Drug Unit of Sandoz Picks Chief Executive
abstract: LEAD: The Sandoz Pharmaceuticals Corporation yesteday named Jacques F. Rejeange as president and chief executive. He succeeds Fred Hassan, who will move to an unspecified position at the American Home Products Corporation.

headline: BRIEFS
abstract: LEAD: * BSR International P.L.C., London, an electronics company, agreed to acquire five businesses from Emerson Electric Co. in exchange for new shares that value the Emerson businesses at $:86 million.

headline: Atari Plans To Divest Retail Unit
abstract: LEAD: The Atari Corporation said today that it planned to dispose of the Federated Group Inc., a consumer electronics retailer it purchased in 1987. As a result, the company said it had established reserves and taken a write-off of more than $100 million, resulting in large losses for the fourth quarter of 1988 and for the year.

headline: Malaysian Coal Deposits
abstract: LEAD: A West German team has found two coal deposits with about 93 million tons of coal worth an estimated $2.56 billion, it was reported Tuesday. The two deposits were found in the Tebulan and Merit South areas of the Malaysian state of Sarawak, The New Straits Times reported, quoting S. P. Chen, director of Sarawak's Geological Survey Department.

headline: Israel Sets Demands on Taba
abstract: LEAD: Israel's inner Cabinet agreed today to demand free access for Israelis to the Taba Red Sea resort and joint ownership of a hotel complex there in exchange for returning the disputed area to Egypt, Cabinet officials said. Israeli, Egyptian and American negotiators will meet Thursday at the luxury hotel at the center of the seven-year border dispute.

headline: Talking Deals; The Proprieties Of 'No Comment'
abstract: LEAD: STOCK MARKET rumors have always been a big problem for the New York Stock Exchange. These days it is an even bigger problem because so many companies are refusing to comment about what may be going on when their stock is moving sharply.

headline: Italy Convicts 7 in Bombing Of Train Fatal to 16 in 1984
abstract: LEAD: A court today convicted seven people, including five organized crime figures, in a 1984 train bombing that killed 16 travelers and wounded more than 200.

headline: Palestinian Rebels Killed In Border Region in Lebanon
abstract: LEAD: Three Palestinian guerrillas on their way to attack Israel were killed today inside Israel's border buffer zone in southern Lebanon, the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army said.

headline: G.M.'s Dispute Over Hughes
abstract: LEAD: The General Motors Corporation has made only two major strategic acquisitions in recent history, and both have proved troublesome. Its $2.5 billion purchase of the Electronic Data Systems Corporation in 1984 led to an embarrassing public dispute with the E.D.S. founder, H. Ross Perot. Now G.M. is embroiled in a potentially costly wrangle over its 1986 purchase of the Hughes Aircraft Company.

headline: Judge Said to Back Popeye's on Offer
abstract: LEAD: A. Copeland Enterprises Inc., the owners of Popeye's Famous Fried Chicken fast-food restaurants, said a Federal judge in Louisiana had ruled that the company could proceed with its $8-a-share offer for Church's Fried Chicken Inc. The ruling reverses a preliminary decision made against Popeye's last week.

headline: To Egypt, Peace Pact Is a Stigma on Its Arab Soul
abstract: LEAD: The destination board at Cairo airport records the departure of flight LY444 most nights at 9:15 P.M., but it does not say where the Israeli airplane is going - to Tel Aviv.

headline: Jordan Acts on Dinar
abstract: LEAD: Jordan forcibly closed offices of moneychangers around the nation today, blaming them for speculating against the weakened dinar. Police locked and sealed the premises of more than 70 exchanges in Amman, the capital, and elsewhere, including exchanges at borders and airports, witnesses said.

headline: Murray Industries Supports Proposal
abstract: LEAD: Murray Industries, the parent of the Murray Chris-Craft Boat Companies, said it had tentatively approved an offer from Genmar Industries to buy a substantial part of the boat maker's assets. Terms were not disclosed. The offer is subject to court and regulatory approval and any higher or better offer, said Mary Glass, a Chris-Craft spokeswoman.

headline: 3 Rescued From Mine That Collapsed in Peru
abstract: LEAD: Rescuers found three buried miners alive today and heard faint tapping inside a dilapidated gold mine where as many as 200 men were trapped in a cave-in, officials said.

headline: Bush Plan On Savings Under Fire
abstract: LEAD: After an almost euphoric reception by Congress last Monday, President Bush's plan to rescue the savings and loan industry is getting somewhat bruised. Lawmakers are complaining that the proposal is short on money, weak on detail and likely to become a budgetary nightmare down the road.

headline: No More 'Steak' for The Post
abstract: LEAD: THE agency that added meat to The New York Post's sizzling image has been banished from the kitchen.

headline: Soviets Report Protests In Georgia in November
abstract: LEAD: Nationalists in Soviet Georgia staged factory sit-ins, demonstrations and hunger strikes to protest constitutional changes that they fear could limit local sovereignty, Pravda said today.

headline: Why Business Turns to Teen-Agers
abstract: LEAD: In the last few years, as America's jobless rate plummeted to the lowest levels since the mid-1970's, ''Hiring'' signs have proliferated at fast-food restaurants, department stores, supermarkets and countless other businesses. Increasingly, those jobs are going to people like Margie Lobaton in Warwick, R.I., and Patrick Gannaway in Huntington Beach, Calif.

headline: Commodore Fills Job Left Vacant Since '87
abstract: LEAD: After reporting strong quarterly earnings this week, Commodore International Ltd. announced yesterday that it had named Mehdi Ali, a managing director at Dillon, Read & Company, as its new president.

headline: Britain, in Talk Aimed at Iran, Calls Rushdie Book Offensive
abstract: LEAD: Two days after Iran threatened to break off diplomatic relations, Britain's Foreign Secretary today sharply distanced the Government from Salman Rushdie's novel ''The Satanic Verses.'' He said the book was not only offensive to Muslims but had also compared Britain to Hitler's Germany.

headline: Israeli Troops on Night Patrol Kill Arab Man
abstract: LEAD: Israeli troops on a night patrol in the occupied West Bank shot and killed a Palestinian man with a plastic bullet on Monday and wounded a second person, Palestinians and the army said today.

headline: BUYOUT BARON: William F. Farley; Taking Over in a One-Company Town
abstract: LEAD: At an emotional rally in the small textile town of Lanett, Ala., last fall, the chairman and chief executive of West Point-Pepperell Inc., the area's largest employer, vowed to keep his company out of the hands of a certain Northern industrialist: William F. Farley.

headline: Jaguar Sales Up in U.S.
abstract: LEAD: Jaguar Cars Inc., the United States subsidiary of Britain's Jaguar P.L.C., said today that its total sales for January were 1,492 units, up 28 percent from the 1,168 units sold a year earlier.

headline: Dollar Slides On Central Banks' Sales
abstract: LEAD: The dollar fell sharply yesterday after another round of concerted dollar-selling by the Federal Reserve and other central banks. It then slipped a bit more after President Bush's inaugural address.

headline: Your Money; Regional Firms: Local Expertise?
abstract: LEAD: If there is one constant - other than luck - that makes for a successful stock investor, it is good information. Not the kind of ''good'' information that leads to clanging jail doors for insider trading, but the kind timely research can provide.

headline: Report Says U.S. War Planes Nearly Hit 6 Passenger Jets
abstract: LEAD: Six United States warplanes on a low-level training flight changed course without warning last Tuesday and flew dangerously close to six passenger jets, a magazine reported today.

headline: Chase Lifts Prime Rate By 1/2 Point
abstract: LEAD: The Chase Manhattan Bank raised its prime lending rate by half a percentage point yesterday afternoon, to 11 1/2 percent, the second increase in less than two weeks.

headline: Taking a Scalpel to Health Costs
abstract: LEAD: There is a general practitioner in Florida who, while he may not realize it, is being watched from Connecticut. Those monitoring his performance do not like what they see.

headline: Accounts
abstract: LEAD: * Creative Hairdressers, Inc., to Della Femina, McNamee WCRS, Inc., Chicago, for its Hair Cuttery salons.

headline: Keeping the Pickle Crunchy
abstract: LEAD: Since man first tossed cucumbers in brine - and savored the sour results - the pickle business has not exactly sparkled with technical innovation. But now a researcher for the Department of Agriculture has developed a patented process to make kosher dills keep their crunch. Some say the development could amount to a small revolution for the $400 million industry.
